<HEAD>Proposal Would Withhold Federal Aid to Promote Anti-Drug War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration is considering withholding governmental benefits such as student loans and public housing assistance to people convicted of drug use, according to a published report. The <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet-level </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, headed by Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, approved the proposals in outline form at a meeting May 27, but they have not yet been presented to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported in Wednesday's editions, citing sources it did not identify. `` We're not trying to be Draconian _ we're not going to kick poor people out of public housing ...,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> quoted one source as saying. `` But at the same time, we're trying to encourage'' state and local governments and colleges to adopt anti-drug programs that will have `` maximum impact.'' The proposals would seek to fight drug abuse by threatening to withhold some federal aid to state and local governments, colleges and universities and other publicly funded institutions that fail to adopt strict, federally approved anti-drug programs, the sources said. One proposal calls for state governments to refuse to issue first-time drivers' licenses to minors who have been convicted of drug use, and the federal government would enforce this by threatening to withhold federal transportation funding, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said. Various federal department and agencies were directed to study the proposals and report back to <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> by Wednesday, the newspaper said. One source told the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> that no objections had been raised and that the proposals probably would be presented to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> within the next few days.
