<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrat <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> staged what was to have been a celebratory appeal for votes on the final night of the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> primary campaign, but the half-hour show was botched when the presidential candidate got stuck in traffic and missed half of it. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> arrived 16 minutes into the half-hour broadcast, which originated at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> station <ORGANIZATION> KTLA </ORGANIZATION> and shown throughout the state at a cost of $ 150,000. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> fell behind schedule on campaign appearances in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> earlier in the the day, then got tied up in traffic jams trying to get to the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> airport. The show opened with rock disc jockey <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasem </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> supporter, announcing that the chair next to him was empty because <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was on his way. The first half of the show was given over to a video montage of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> campaign appearances. <PERSON> Kasem </PERSON> filled time waiting for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> by interviewing <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s state campaign manager, producing some tortured exchanges. Then came a second video montage, featuring some of the same footage already shown. Finally, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> appeared. The candidate, appearing calm but his face glistening with perspiration, talked about the issues that he has stressed in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> _ offshore oil drilling and environmental concerns as well as devoting defense funding to peaceful application in space and science instead. He also highlighted his anti-drug message and his call for an end to gang warfare. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told <PERSON> Kasem </PERSON> he had a `` day of big crowds, lots of excitement, but mostly of touching people's hearts.'' Earlier in the day, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, shifting the focus toward thd Democratic convention this summer, said Monday he will go to the convention mat with <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> unless the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> front-runner comes around to his position on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> accused <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> of proceeding too `` cautiously and conservatively'' in refusing to agree with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> should be declared a terrorist nation. `` If he will not bend on that matter, we'll simply meet on the floor at <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said during a call-in radio news conference. The tough talk was the most pointed language <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has used in discussing his intentions for the convention. `` The matter needs to be resolved in the committee or in platform hearings or on the convention floor,'' he told reporters later. He indicated he will put up a fight for his platform issues but will do so within the framework of party rules, leaving unclear just how hard a bargain he will drive. `` We can resolve our differences within the context of our party and not in the streets _ and that's growth,'' he said at one point. He also said that at the convention he would `` use the rules to have fair rules'' _ a reference to his contention that the popular vote is not fairly reflected in the delegate count and so delegate-selection procedures should be changed. As for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> contends the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should subject that nation to the trade sanctions applied to other countries it has put on its terrorist list such as <LOCATION>