<HEAD>Rare French Donkey Expecting Baby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLIVENHAIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Sonnette </PERSON>, a rare French donkey who narrowly escaped a government death sentence four years ago, is expecting its first offspring. `` She looks like she swallowed a barrel. She looks like she wants to have it any minute,'' said <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanderlip </PERSON>, who owns the donkey with her husband, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanderlip </PERSON>. The Vanderlips, both veterinarians at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Sonnette </PERSON> successfully mated with a 3-year-old of the same breed about a year ago and should deliver her first foal later this month. Sonnette is one of four donkeys the Vanderlips imported to their northern <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> farm from the <LOCATION> Poitou </LOCATION> region of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1984 and 1985. In 1984, federal agriculture inspectors almost put <PERSON> Sonnette </PERSON>, a member of an endangered species, to death because the donkey failed an equine blood test for communicable diseases. A public outcry ensued over the plans to destroy the animal, and officials changed their mind when the Vanderlips and other experts showed the test given was n't suitable for a specialized variety such as the Poitou donkey. A test designed for the rare donkey was then given to <LOCATION> Sonnette </LOCATION> and it was released from quarantine after being certified as healthy and free of disease. Since then, the <PERSON> Vanderlips </PERSON> have imported three other rare Poitou donkeys, including the father-to-be, <LOCATION> Tartarin </LOCATION>. The Vanderlips hope to establish a herd to help the save the breed from extinction. About 45 Poitou donkeys remain in existence, said Mrs. <PERSON> Vanderlip </PERSON>, who learned about the species while studying veterinary medicine in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> several years ago. <PERSON> Sonnette </PERSON> has been separated from the other donkeys and will remain alone with the foal until the baby is weaned at 4 months to 6 months of age. <PERSON> Tartarin </PERSON> also will be kept away from <LOCATION> Sonnette </LOCATION> as well as the foal because male donkeys can become agitated around small creatures and may even kill them, Mrs. <PERSON> Vanderlip </PERSON> said.
