 Too many doctors hesitate to give good advice about disease prevention and promotion of good health, perhaps because they're preoccupied with high-tech medicine, <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Surgeon General <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> said. `` We seem at times to be more interested in transplanting diseased hearts and lungs than we are in teaching people not to smoke in order to prevent heart and lung disease from occuring in the first place,'' he said Monday. <PERSON> Koop </PERSON>, speaking to graduates of the <ORGANIZATION> Kirksville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Osteopathic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, said doctors are under greater pressure to slow down if not reverse the rising cost of health care _ sometimes by making judgments based on cost rather than on the basis of good medicine.
