<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crews filming scenes for a movie about bat-wielding principal <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> have disrupted classes and graduation plans, but some students said the film also has generated excitement. `` They moved our classes. So what, it does n't mean they are going to stop,'' said <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sousa </PERSON>, an Eastside High junior who is an extra in the movie. `` Mostly the only reason you sit in class by now is to go over your review sheets. Books have already been collected.'' Several students and parents have complained that <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> crews filming `` Lean on Me'' forced a change in graduation sites, <LOCATION> Passaic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> schools Superintendent <PERSON> Melindo </PERSON> <PERSON> Persi </PERSON> said Monday. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, who gained national attention for a get-tough approach to education that includes wielding bullhorns and baseball bats in hallways, could not be reached for comment. Calls left with his secretary Monday were not returned. As the 97-member film crew built sets, sprayed graffiti over lockers and filmed a scene with actor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillaume </PERSON>, students hanging out after school said they saw only a positive impact from the movie. Sophomore <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, an extra waiting to be called, said students in the movie have been given plenty of time to do their homework, and tutors are available if needed. She said she hopes to parlay her movie appearance into greater roles in the future. `` I was excited because now there is a chance for us to be noticed,'' she said. Some school officials, however, were worried there are too many distractions at a time of year when important exams are held. `` My concern is just for the kids,'' said <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Brightman </PERSON>, a school board member. `` I'd like them t