<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Virgil Oliver</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Virgil </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 72, who played the mean little kids `` Butch'' and `` Tuffy'' in early `` Our Gang'' movie shorts, died Friday. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> played the bully for about a year in 1925, earning $ 7.50 a day, before he outgrew the role. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> had two other non-speaking acting jobs in films and then decided to move on to a new career in real estate.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Edward Quade</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAGUNA HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaumberg </PERSON> <PERSON> Quade </PERSON>, a founder of the methodical problem-solving method known as `` systems analysis,'' died Saturday. He was 79. <PERSON> Quade </PERSON> joined the research organization when it was founded in 1948 and retired in 1973. His 1968 book, `` Systems Analysis and Policy Planning: Applications in Defense,'' defined systems analysis as `` a systematic approach to helping a decision-maker choose a course of action by investigating his full problem, searching out objectives and alternatives, and comparing them in the light of their consequences.'' <PERSON> Quade </PERSON>'s books applied systems analysis to military problems and later to broader public policy issues.
