<HEAD>Farm Wives Lash Back at Critics of Pesticide Use</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Concern over the hazards of chemical pesticides has gone too far, according to members of a farm women's organization meeting in the nation's capital `` We feed our families with the food we grow; we're not going to feed them poison,'' says <PERSON> Mildred </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Hale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. She is here for the sixth annual <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> meeting of Women Involved in Farm Economics, an organization that brings together farm women from across the country to wrestle with agricultural issues. The group frequently has focused on the intricacies of world markets for farm commodities and federal payment programs. But pressure for congressional action on the pesticide issue prompted an environmental seminar as well this year. Many crops produced in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and overseas are sprayed with pesticides, some of which the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has linked with cancer and other serious health problems. The two speakers at the farm women's session were representatives of industries that have been major targets of environmental criticism. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Early </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, focused on pesticides, while, <PERSON> Vickie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, a legislative analyst with a utility company, discussed the acid rain issue. Early said he doubted that regulatory legislation recently produced by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> would be sent to the president's desk this year. He said so many loose ends remain to be tied up in other committees that it will be `` close to impossible to get all these things pulled together.'' `` To do all that before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> goes home and tries to get re-elected _ and they will do that earlier this year _ I just do n't think you can get it all done this year,'' he said His organization is supporting the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s bill but is opposing separate legislation cosponsored by <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., and Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON>, R-Minn It would impose stringent standards for clean groundwater, which provides the major supply of drinking water for millions of Americans but has in some areas been found to be laced with pesticides. There may be an effort to attach the <PERSON> Leahy-Durenberger </PERSON> plan to the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s blueprint for revising the Federal Insecticide, Fungicide and Rodenticide Act. After the session, a number of members of the farm women's group agreed to discuss their attitudes toward pesticides at an impromptu roundtable discussion. <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, the group's president, recalled how she drove into a farmers market near her home town of <LOCATION> Royal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, not long ago with a truckload of vegetables. Nearby another farmer was parked, advertising that his vegetables were organically grown _ without the use of pesticides. Customers were interested at first, she says. But that changed. `` He had on his truck `` organicially grown'' and as soon as they found the worms on his vegetables, they walked away,'' she recalled. `` They want absolutely perfect products and we have supplied them with them,'' said <PERSON> Naioma </PERSON> <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sterling </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, a wheat and cattle producer. Environmentalists, she said, `` are not looking at the total, full picture'' and often have `` a biased and slanted view.'' The notion that farmers are poisoning the land with toxic chemicals is absurd, she said. `` Our families depend on it. Our futures and our childrens' futures depend on it. `` My husband really respects the chemicals and is very careful how he uses them,'' said <PERSON> Merlina </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Almira </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>. She also recalled a trip to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> last year to inspect irrigation systems used in that country She saw `` beautiful vegetables'' grown there without benefit of pesticides. `` But those same vegetables would not be bought in a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> store,'' she said. The reason? Too many flaws caused by pests. The women condemned the notion that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law should attempt to eliminate all risk from the use of pesticides. Instead, they said, pesticide use should be likened to the use of certain drugs that are beneficial in treating illnesses but sometimes have side effects, or to automobiles, which are certain to mean highway fatalities but provide vital transportation. They also pointed the finger at pesticides banned here that are being used overseas on crops that are then brought into this country. `` They're being used in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and hauled across the border,'' said <PERSON> Clara </PERSON> <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> <PERSON> Spivey </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, cotton and peanut grower.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Farm Belt senator clashed with administration officials after they rejected both his bill to increase the nation's commitment to agricultural research and similar recommendations from an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> task force `` You're rejecting the recommendations of your own task force,'' Sen. <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.D. </LOCATION>, said Monday after <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> voiced opposition to the proposals. The bill would set up an independent corporation to make research grants and provide federal funding for it. The price tag envisioned by <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> would be $ 100 million. The task force recommended $ 1 billion. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> deputy assistant secretary for science and education, made clear that the department was opposed. `` We do disagree with the amount that was involved and we do disagree with the mechanisms that were involved, and that's our privilege as it was their privilege to make those recommendations,'' <PERSON> Long </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> already supports a sizeable, government-operated agricultural research program, and <PERSON> Long </PERSON> said <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON>'s legislation would add a new layer of bureaucracy. He also said the administration would not back research grants that could not be reviewed by the secretary of agriculture.
