<HEAD>Delegates Flock To Dukakis As He Heads Over The Top</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> closed to within 200 delegates of locking up the Democratic presidential nomination even before the first votes were counted in today's season-ending primaries, boosted by a surge of about 180 in the last week. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> picked up 75 of those new delegates on Monday alone, some prodded into declaring their support by his campaign staff and others attracted by the near-gravitational force that surrounds a winner. `` He's been on a roll,'' said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Brophy </PERSON>, deputy director of delegate selection for the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign. `` He's shown election success week after week after week,'' she said. `` It casts a very favorable light on <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>.'' Much of the surge came courtesy of `` super delegates,'' the party leaders and elected officials who have heavily favored <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, to the chagrin of <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor also has been converting delegates who had been pledged to the suspended candidacies of Sens. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>. On Monday, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON>, a staunch supporter of <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, switched to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and brought the bulk of his state's 65-member delegation with him This came two days after <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> said he would continue to support <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>. And in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> on Monday, Gov. Rose Mofford and four other `` super delegates'' moved to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> from the uncommitted ranks, where they had been since former Gov. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON> dropped out of the presidential race. By its own estimates, the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign has moved within striking distance of the 2,081 delegates needed to clinch the nomination. With fewer than 200 delegates to go, the campaign expects to take at least 280 of the 466 delegates at stake in today's primaries in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. The intensity of the operation to contact and win delegates has picked up as the primary season draws to a close. Delegates are told that `` the governor would appreciate it very much if they would get into the count earlier rather than later,'' Ms. <PERSON> Brophy </PERSON> said. `` The goal of all of this is to take the pressure off <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> after June 7 so he can go about the process of building a coalition for the general election,'' she said. Another incentive is the memory of 1984, when <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> finished the final round of primaries without enough delegates to lock up the nomination and spent an extra day pleading with a handful of delegates to put him over the top. Some members of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' staff, including delegate chief <PERSON> Tad </PERSON> <PERSON> Devine </PERSON>, worked for <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> four years ago. Of the 178 delegates moved into the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> column in the last week, roughly half were super delegates, the party leaders and politicians who automatically hold seats at the convention, and the rest were delegates picked through the primaries and caucuses who had been uncommitted or pledged to other candidates. `` I think that the advantage that we have is that we have been on the phones with these people so long and there is a real strong bond between some of these people and the campaign,'' Ms. <PERSON> Brophy </PERSON> said. By Monday, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> held support from more than 321 of the 643 super delegates, while <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was backed by just 54, of whom 42 are black, according to The Associated Press delegate count. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has complained that the super delegates have disproportionately favored <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and hinted he may challenge the rules that created them. He also has indicated he may launch a convention challenge against the rules that allow some states to pick other delegates in a manner that does not reflect the results of the states' primaries.
