<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A joint national proposal by the governors of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to reduce acid rain shows <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> `` is finally reading the writing on the wall'' and seeking help to curb pollution from its coal-fired power plants, a congressman says. On Monday, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> made public their proposal to reduce polluting sulfur dioxide emissions from utility sources by 10 million tons by the year 2003. The plan calls for authorizing $ 900 million a year from the federal government to finance up to 50 percent of the capital costs. Most of that money would come from having the oil industry take over the cost of filling the <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>. The polluters themselves would have to raise about $ 900 million a year under the deal. Rep. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sikorski </PERSON>, D-Minn., said it represents `` significant progress'' anytime <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> can agree on acid rain Sulfur dioxide emissions from the burning of coal have been blamed as a major cause of acid rain, which environmentalists say is destroying waters and woodlands in the Northeast. Much of the sulfur dioxide comes from coal-burning power plants along the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sikorski </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, is the main sponsor of an acid rain control bill pending in committee. His bill would mandate a 10-million-ton reduction in emissions by 1998. `` This agreement shows that there is renewed seriousness about dealing with the issue,'' <PERSON> Sikorski </PERSON> said. `` It indicates that <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> is finally reading the writing on the wall. This could be their last good chance at legislation that assists them with their cleanup costs.'' But the proposal drew fire from other lawmakers. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said that while he is encouraged by the dialogue between <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on acid rain, he sees nothing new in the `` The key element of any effort to deal with acid rain has to be time,'' said <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>. `` And this proposal does not allow enough time for the development of clean-coal technologies. Coal is essential to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s national security, and we can not afford to adopt an acid rain policy that would devastate the coal industry.'' Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Luken </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, said the proposal would hurt <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and accused <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> of not speaking for Ohioans on the issue. Regardless of the financing `` gimmicks,'' said <PERSON> Luken </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> consumers `` will pay millions of dollars and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> will lose thousands of jobs for no known benefit.'' <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, next to coal-rich <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, has a significant coal-mining industry. Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON>, R-Vt., said he believes the proposal represents a breakthrough because it is the first time a major emitter of sulfur dioxide, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, has attempted to come to grips with the acid rain problem <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON>, who is ranking Repub