<HEAD>Japan Says It Is Trimming Trade Surplus, Urges U.S. To Do Its Share</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is trimming its huge trade surplus by expanding imports and stepping up overseas investment, the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> said today. But the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must do its part for the world economy by easing its budget and trade deficits, the ministry said in a report summing up <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s foreign trade in 1987. It also said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> should play a bigger role in Asian development through direct investment and importing more of the region's manufactured goods The report, issued annually since 1949, praises ongoing structural changes that have improved access to the Japanese market for foreign exporters of manufactured goods. `` Manufactured imports are increasing rapidly and the distribution system in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is undergoing a change,'' said <PERSON> Atsushi </PERSON> <PERSON> Oi </PERSON>, head of the ministry's <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus fell in fiscal 1987 for the first time in six years, from $ 101.65 billion in 1986 to $ 94.28 billion, according to Japanese figures. Still, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continued to climb, hitting $ 4.9 billion in December 1987 from $ 4.7 billion a year earlier, the latest government figures show. <PERSON> Oi </PERSON> said increased exports of capital goods to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> contributed to the increase. Capital goods exports are rising as Japanese firms send equipment to set up <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production facilities. `` Secondly, and this has a bigger share, is that American companies look to excellent capital goods exports from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and install these in their plants,'' <PERSON> Oi </PERSON> said. Finance Minister <PERSON> Kiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> said exports bound for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will fall from the present 40 percent share of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s total to 25-30 percent as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> restructures its export-driven economy toward domestic demand He did not give a time frame. The trade ministry report says Japanese imports grew by 9.3 percent in 1987 over the previous year, while export volume rose only 0.3 percent. <PERSON> Oi </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can lessen its trade deficit by cutting down on excessive consumer demand, expanding production facilities and revamping its export policy. The report says the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit hit $ 171.2 billion in 1987, up $ 15 billion over 1986. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> rose by a meager 8.4 percent in 1987, but those from <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s newly industrialized countries of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> soared by 50.3 percent, the report says. The white paper is cautious about the future of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s restructuring It says that while imports are growing along with domestic demand, nations awash in surplus funds like <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> `` must expand imports and provide a stable supply of capital to debtor nations.'' `` The role of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> from now on is to help <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> countries create ... a region of development that is open to the rest of the world,'' <PERSON> Oi </PERSON> said.
