<HEAD>Bomb Kills Soldier, Wounds Four as Indians Begin Pullout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Separatist Tamil rebels blew up an <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> army jeep today, killing one soldier and wounding four just hours before hundreds of Indian troops began boarding nearby ships to return home. One Sri Lankan officer called the attack `` a show of strength'' by the rebels, who have fought a five-year war for greater autonomy. Indian officials said their at least partial troop withdrawal would go on as scheduled. Sri Lankan military officers said the jeep was patrolling about six miles south of the port city of <LOCATION> Trincomalee </LOCATION> when the rebels detonated a mine under it. Just a few hours later, Indian sodliers began pulling out as scheduled in <LOCATION> Trincomalee </LOCATION>, 140 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. `` It was a show of strength by the rebels,'' said the Sri Lankan officer, who can not be identified under briefing rules. `` It's a slap in the face.'' The Indian High Commission, or embassy, confirmed the attack but gave no details. But Deputy High Commissioner <PERSON> Nirupam </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> said the attack did not affect the pullout of the first contingent of Indian peacekeeping soldiers and weapons, including Soviet-made T-72 tanks and 105mm and 120mm artillery. At least 3,000 of the estimated 50,000 Indian soldiers in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> were scheduled to depart for home today by ship from <LOCATION> Trincomalee </LOCATION>. Indian Defense Minister K.C. <PERSON> Pant </PERSON> said last week that `` excess troops and armor'' would be sent home but announced no firm timetable for a complete withdrawal. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> began sending in soldiers last July to enforce a peace accord aimed at ending the civil war on this island off its southern coast. The deployment increased in October after rebels renounced the peace plan, refused to surrender their weapons and resumed fighting. The Indian troops, stationed only in the north and east where Tamils are in the majority, had been ordered to disarm the rebel fighters. Predominantly Hindu Tamils comprise 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people and claim they are discriminated against by the mostly <PERSON> Buddhist </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinhalese </PERSON>, who constitute 75 percent of the population and control the government and military. The peace accord reached by the <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and the Sri Lankan government of President <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> calls for election of district councils to give the nation's nine provinces greater autonomy. Elections have been held in six provinces so far, and voting is scheduled for Thursday in the predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Sinhalese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION>. Balloting has been postponed in the Tamil-dominated Northern and Eastern provinces because of the fighting. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, a major regional power, negotiated the peace accord and agreed to police it partly for fear of sympathies that its own 60 million Tamils feel for the rebel cause. Though the <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> have been unable to stem the fighting, a string of recent victories led them to agree with <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> on at least a partial pullout. The Indian presence has been criticized by many Sinhalese, who view it as a threat to Sri Lankan independence.
