<HEAD>Feds Halt Offshore Oil Lease Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opponents of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's proposal for extensive oil leasing off the <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> coast claimed credit for the decision to suspend the plan, but said they remain wary it wo n't be scuttled Interior Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> late Monday made the announcement to halt work on the proposal to lease 1.1 million offshore acres. The decision effectively pushes the sale back at least until to August 1989. <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON>'s action came on the eve of the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> primary and a day after Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> softened his pro-drilling stance and called for the offshore plan to be delayed. `` I take that as good news,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, a one-time <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oilman who previously had expressed unconditional support for drilling, said when informed of <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON>'s decision while campaigning in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Democratic presidential hopefuls <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> have advocated stopping all offshore drilling. `` This is an attempt to try to get <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> off the hook,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Charter </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lobbyist who represents <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> coastal communties in their fight against the drilling. He said the announcement also could be an effort to prevent <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> from imposing a one-year moratorium on the sale. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is scheduled on Wednesday to consider such a plan to delay leasing until 1990. Anmother critic, <LOCATION> Humboldt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Supervisor <PERSON> Wesley </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesbro </PERSON>, said, `` We've succeeded beyond our wildest dreams in making this an issue of importance to the national campaign.'' However, he added, `` Temporary political delays are great, but they're not what we're looking for.'' <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> said in a statement that `` it appears that no valid public purpose would be served by preparation and publication of a final environmental impact statement containing a proposed course of action for Lease Sale 91.'' The department estimates that the area proposed for the lease could contain up to 790 million barrels of oil _ a two-month supply for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ and between 820 billion and 1.5 trillion cubic feet of natural gas. It says there is a 50-50 chance of finding the petroleum. The proposed lease sale of tracts off <LOCATION> Mendocino </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Humboldt </LOCATION> counties had been tentatively scheduled for February 1989, pending a decision by the next administration. At least six months is needed between the report's conclusion and a sale, due to hearings and other preparatory work. Department spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Prosperi </PERSON> said the environmental report could have been prepared as early as August. <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> indicated he was reluctant to take the action. `` I believe we do not have to choose between development of offshore oil or protection of the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> coast,'' he said. `` Experience shows we can have both.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had criticized <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> earlier Monday for `` coming around'' to his latest position `` kind of late.'' And, the Democratic front-runner said: `` It's easy to say, ` We'll delay it until after the election. What does that mean?'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s aides acknowledged that his statement on Sunday represented a major concession to strong bipartisan environmental sentiments in the state. `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> recognizes the importance of environmental and quality-of-life issues in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>,'' said chief of staff <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>. Charter said that if <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> becomes president, <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON>'s action represents `` only a six-month reprieve for Lease Sale 91.'' The lobbyist said the vice president has not made a clear commitment to do away with the sale, noting that `` There are a lot of qualifiers in his statement.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said it supported <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON>'s decision for `` a reasonable delay. `` We're political realists,'' said <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Hume </PERSON>, a spokesman for the industry group. `` Right now, it is clear that the people of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> _ especially the people of <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> _ are not comfortable with the environmental studies that now exist.''
