<HEAD>World of Play Can Be Harsh for Migrant Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WIMAUMA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While most kids spend their time playing with toy trucks and tractors, migrant children often play in the hot, dusty strawberry fields of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> with the real thing. The harsh world of heavy equipment and soil-cutting tools can mean deep gashing wounds, burns, severed limbs and sometimes, loss of life. It was in one of those strawberry patches on an April day last year that 7-year-old <PERSON> Karla </PERSON> <PERSON> Polanco </PERSON> nearly lost her leg as she dangled it over the rear of a truck while her parents picked strawberries nearby. Somebody wanted the truck moved, so her 12-year-old playmate hopped in the front seat, shifted into reverse and slammed <PERSON> Karla </PERSON>'s leg between the rig and a trailer And last week, 5-year-old <PERSON> Fidencio </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaurequi </PERSON>'s right arm was ripped off at a <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> farm when he accidentally stuck it in a tomato sorting machine while his mother worked nearby. Doctors were unable to reattach the limb because the injury was so severe. The boy was listed in good condition Monday at <ORGANIZATION> Tampa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. With their parents working in the fields from sunrise to sunset and few available day-care services, hundreds of migrant children are left to fend for themselves in empty homes or busy fields. `` We see the evidence all the time _ cut fingers because the children stuck them in a fan, burns because the children were hungry and tried to cook something to eat while their parents were off at work,'' said <PERSON> Lourdes </PERSON> <PERSON> Villanueva </PERSON>, a former migrant who runs a day-care program in <LOCATION> Plant </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. In the camps where migrants live, stories abound of children maimed or killed in accidents in the fields. Many accidents go unreported to authorities as families move on to other states, migrants say. `` I remember this one woman some years back who brought a 6-month-old baby out into the fields,'' said <PERSON> Concha </PERSON> <PERSON> Calderon </PERSON>, who has four children. `` The baby got too hot out there and died. She did n't have anybody to watch it.'' There is no reliable estimate of the largely undocumented migrant farmworker population in southern <LOCATION> Hillsborough </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, but social workers guess there are between 25,000 and 45,000 people. The <ORGANIZATION> Redlands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Migrant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the county's primary provider of migrant day care, has only 668 available spots for migrant children and a waiting list of 575. There are many more out there, but they do n't qualify for programs like Migrant Headstart because they did n't travel as farmworkers during the year, experts say. `` Even a few years ago I would say there were a lot of workers still traveling back and forth, from state to state,'' Ms. <PERSON> Villanueva </PERSON> said. `` But now I think more are just staying here and working odd jobs during the summer because you just ca n't make as much money traveling any more.''
