<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, who meets with the Soviet foreign minister this week, chided <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for seeking a political deal to improve relations but referred to <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> as a `` great leader.'' `` The Soviets keep hinting that they will renew diplomatic relations with us if we agree to their proposal for an international conference on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said in a speech here Monday. `` I do n't believe we should pay for the resumption of diplomatic relations. They broke them and they should renew them.'' In an interview published in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who has instituted reforms in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` My observation is, to bring a new message, a new idea to such a great country, it could be done only by a great leader,'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> told the Times. Less than two years ago, the leader of the hard-line <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> party described the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> as `` old wine in new bottles.'' In his speech, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> reiterated his opposition to an international conference, which also was included in a <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> peace plan put forth by Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> in a visit to the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> this week. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, who met with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> on Sunday, said it is an `` illusion ... that an outside power can suc