` Anyone who knows anything about the statement knows it was said tongue-in-cheek at a private meeting.'' On Monday, former top gubernatorial aide <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> testified that she warned <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> during the campaign to distance himself from the man who loaned him the money, <LOCATION> Tempe </LOCATION> developer <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfson </PERSON>. Also, former <ORGANIZATION> Mecham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Vern </PERSON> <PERSON> Gasser </PERSON> read the jury a set of notes he took during a committee meeting in the fall of 1986. The notes say `` show <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> borrowed money'' and `` do n't show borrowed money,'' and some say they appear to reflect a discussion on whether to disclose the loan. However, <PERSON> Gasser </PERSON> said he could n't recall the conversation or what the notes meant. <ORGANIZATION> Maricopa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> allowed <PERSON> Gasser </PERSON> to read the notes despite defense objections. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> is charged with six felony counts of perjury, willful concealment and filing false documents, and faces up to 22 years in prison if convicted on all counts. <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> faces three similar counts and up to 9 -LCB- years in prison if convicted. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> took office in January 1987. He was removed from office April 4 when the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> convicted him of two unrelated impeachment counts.
