<SECOND>PM-Computer Glitch,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Glitch Causes Data To Vanish From Air Traffic Controller
Screens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Critical information is disappearing momentarily from air traffic controllers' screens in airports for <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> because of a computer glitch, a newspaper reported today. Information on altitude, airspeed, aircraft types, call signs and destinations vanish from radar screens for up to 20 seconds, said the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> Morning News, quoting <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> officials. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials do not believe the error in a computer program presents a hazard to safety, <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Parrent </PERSON>, assistant air traffic manager at <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, said Monday. `` The radar has not failed,'' <PERSON> Parrent </PERSON> said. `` The primary target is still there.'' The radar image and a four-digit number assigned to each aircraft, known as a `` target'' by controllers, remain on the screen. Controllers are concerned about the glitch and are monitoring the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s progress in fixing it, said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullin </PERSON>, a local representative of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Controllers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's a new program and there are some software problems,'' he said. `` I do n't think that's anything unusual. We're not totally comfortable with it, but they're working hard on the system.'' The information disappears when the program `` detects a glitch in the system,'' <PERSON> Parrent </PERSON> said. When information is about to disappear, an alarm sounds, and controllers have up to five seconds to write down the information or memorize it, <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials told the Morning News. Controllers handle up to 10 aircraft at a time. The new program offers many features that improve the margin of safety, and `` bugs'' will be worked out, <PERSON> Parrent </PERSON> said. However, the newspaper said some aviation experts and controllers voiced concern that, although horizontal distance between aircraft still can be tracked on the screen, the glitch could cause problems. The risk is exacerbated if the problem occurs when aircraft are in a holding pattern because of bad weather, said <PERSON> Len </PERSON> <PERSON> Nahmi </PERSON>, a California-based airline captain and air safety investigator. It is common for aircraft to be in holding patterns with altitude separations of 1,000 feet in weather that severely limits visibility, <PERSON> Nahmi </PERSON> said. If a pilot deviated from an assigned altitude when information disappeared, the controller would be unable to detect the change, and a collision would be likely, he said. <PERSON> Parrent </PERSON> acknowleged the glitches have made some controllers uneasy. `` It does cause tense moments in the control room,'' he said. `` But we would not run that program if there was a derogation of safety.''
