<HEAD>Defense Secretary Urges Japan to Increase Defense Spending</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> praised the Japanese government for taking on a greater share of its own defense, but urged it to contribute more toward Western security. Speaking to the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> on Monday, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> noted that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has in this decade taken on defense of sea-lanes up to 1,000 miles offshore and begun a five-year procurement plan of beefing up its forces. He said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> had done away with its self-imposed limit of spending just 1 percent of its gross national product on defense and that the government had also pledged to pay all non-salary allowances and expenses for Japanese workers on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases here by 1990. `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> does more than it often gets credit for,'' he said. `` I want to make equally clear today that still more remains to be done.'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> urged <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to increase defense spending, since the current program provides for what he called `` the minimum capability <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> needs to fulfill the defense obligations it has assumed.'' <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> also should increase its financial support for maintaining <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel stationed here, which costs the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government $ 3 billion annually, he said. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> also called on <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to boost overseas economic aid to such developing nations such as <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, which he called `` nations in which aid could advance our overall security.'' He said the West should strengthen controls on its exports to the East to keep its technological lead over the Soviet bloc and should not be lulled by last week's superpower summit in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` Until we see some tangible changes we should not change our policies,'' he said. `` We are still facing a serious military threat.''
