<HEAD>Demonstrators Block Demolition of Buildings Around Golden Temple</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At least 1,000 demonstrators today blocked the government from wrecking buildings around the Golden Temple to create a security corridor free of hiding places for Sikh militants, authorities said. The crowd gathered on a road and prevented construction vehicles from moving in to demolish the buildings within 30 yards of the holiest shrine of the Sikh religion. Sikh militants have used the temple as a base in their battle for an independent homeland. Militants shot and killed a Sikh couple at a village near <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> on Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said. The killings raised to 1,259 the number of people killed this year in attacks blamed on Sikh radicals. Many of the victims have been members of the majority Hindu community, but the militants have also targeted moderate Sikhs. Most of the demonstrators in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> were tenants of the affected buildings, an <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> district government official said. The demonstrators were demanding that they be provided alternate housing before they were evicted, said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. He said senior government officials were negotiating with the demonstrators. `` The demolitions will not begin until the problem is resolved,'' he said. Plans for the security corridor were launched after a 10-day police siege of the temple ended on May 18. More than 200 militants surrendered to police during the siege that left 46 people dead, including 41 suspected radicals and five civilians caught in crossfire.. Police found it difficult to maintain a cordon around the shrine because the maze of alleys, shops and houses next to the complex provided cover for radicals <PERSON> Sarbjeet </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, the top government officer in the district, said workers would demolish 522 properties by the end of the year and create a corridor 1.7 miles in circumference. The entire project, scheduled to be completed within two years, was expected to cost $ 115 million, which would include expenses to buy the land and relocate families and businesses, he said. Sikhs form 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people but are in a majority in northern <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state, where <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> is. Sikh militants have been agitating since 1982 for an independent homeland in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. They say they are discriminated against by <PERSON> Hindus </PERSON>, who comprise 80 percent of the country's population.
