<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> was re-elected speaker of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s parliament today, consolidating his hold on political and military power. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s re-election came five days after <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> named him commander-in-chief of the armed forces in the wake of two major battlefield defeats in the war against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, said 187 of the 192 parliamentary deputies whose credentials have been approved since elections in April and May voted for <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>. Five abstained. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, 53, has been speaker since 1980. Radicals, including many <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> supporters, made sweeping gains in the elections at the expense of conservatives, who have blocked economic reforms. The credentials of other elected deputies in the 270-seat Majlis, or parliament, have either been passed to an investigating committee for scrutiny following objections from other deputies or have not yet been approved, <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> is also <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s representative on the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which determines <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s strategy in the 7 -LCB- - year war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> He sits on the Council for the Expediency of State Decrees, formed earlier this year by <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> to push radical economic reforms through parliament. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> has strong links with the <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, which is now more powerful than the Iranian army. The 87-year-old <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, patriarch of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s Islamic revolution, has been reported in poor health. Speculation that his condition was deteriorating was heightened when he relinquished his constitutional position as commander-in-chief to <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, a middle-ranking cleric. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> has designated a senior cleric, <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein-Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Montazeri </PERSON>, as his successor. But many leading figures, including <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, oppose <PERSON> Montazeri </PERSON>. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s appointment underlined that <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, who has long been close to the patriarch, retains his confidence and is being groomed to hold great power in the post-Khomeini era. The election was the most fiercely contested since the Islamic revolution toppled the <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON> in 1979. The gains in parliament by the radicals, supported by <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, prompted allegations by some prominent conservatives who failed to win re-election that the polling was rigged. It sharpened divisions between radicals, seeking a centralized state-run economy, and the conservatives, who are backed by the wealthy merchant class. The elections touched off clashes between <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> supporters backed by the Revolutionary Guards and protesters in several cities, diplomatic sources reported. Several people were reported killed when the guards opened fire on demonstrators. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s best known opposition politician, former Prime Minister <PERSON> Mehdi </PERSON> <PERSON> Bazargan </PERSON>, distributed an open letter last week accusing <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> of `` erroneous policies'' in the war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and making the <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> an object of hate around the world. Reports reaching <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Bazargan </PERSON>'s criticism triggered a wave of arrests, but it was not known if <PERSON> Bazargan </PERSON> himself had been detained. <PERSON> Bazargan </PERSON>'s small <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> is the only opposition faction permitted to function openly in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and has been constantly harassed by <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> militants in recent years.
