<HEAD>Striking Writers Schedule More Contract Talks With Producers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Striking scriptwriters ended a 12-hour negotiating session with television producers early today, scheduling a fifth straight day of talks as the walkout enters its 14th week. `` We're not characterizing how the meeting went,'' <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> said early today when asked if the continuing talks meant some hope for a breakthrough. The latest session, at the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> headquarters, ended at 2 a.m. today, Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> said. The next round of talks was scheduled for 1:30 this afternoon, she added. The two sides began meeting Friday. Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> declined to comment on the issues discussed. The writers walked out March 7 in a dispute centering on payments or residuals for reruns of one-hour television shows. Demand for such programs in rerun, or syndication, is declining, and the producers want to tie payments to a show's success in the rerun market. The two sides also have been at odds over writers' demands for more creative control over changes made in scripts during filming and more on - and off-screen credit The guild has signed full-term contracts with about 80 independent producers, but the alliance contends none of its large members has signed and the producers who did defect employ only a fraction of the writers.
