<HEAD>Student Posters Criticize Government, Demand Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Political discontent among <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> students broke into the open today as students put up illegal posters demanding democracy and criticizing government corruption. Dozens of anonymous posters blanketed bulletin boards on campus and spilled onto nearby buildings, some with large characters scrawled in black paint on sheets of newspaper and others written in tiny characters on notebook pages. `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> faces an all-out crisis,'' said one poster. `` The most basic human rights are imperiled.'' Several posters demanded a more open press, complaining that Chinese often learn about events in their own country through the foreign media. One quoted the preamble to the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Declaration of Independence, with its defense of `` life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness.'' Students said they planned to march Wednesday from campus to <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, the symbolic center of power in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, to dramatize their demands. Street marches are illegal without police permission. A graduate student at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> slain last week in a brawl outside a liquor store. On Friday, about 1,000 students marched to <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> and met with officials to demand improved security and the arrest of the killers. Police arrested six suspects within 48 hours of the killing. Since Friday, hundreds of students have gathered nightly around campus bulletin boards, holding debates and encouraging each other to draw a larger lesson from the killing. `` People are concerned about more than just this incident,'' said one girl. `` They want to do something for the living.'' Several times in recent months university students have put up posters criticizing government bureaucracy and demanding more state funds for education. The new posters repeated those themes, but also demanded democracy and freedom for the first time since pro-democracy protests swept <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in the winter of 1986-87. Those protests, in which thousands of students marched through <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and other major cities, led to a government crackdown on liberalism and the ouster of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON> for his alleged tolerance toward the students. Students since have been careful not to raise the themes of democracy and freedom. A <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> freshman said today that students are divided over whether agitation now will help or hurt the cause of democracy. `` The <ORGANIZATION> 7th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was the most democratic ever,'' he said, referring to the national legislative session held in March and April, at which delegates were encouraged for the first time to debate selected issues. `` We see democracy moving forward slowly. But if conditions become upset, the government will again rule with a firm hand,'' he said. `` Perhaps the steps we take will not lead us to our goals _ perhaps just the opposite.'' Other students acknowledged that they lack the support of wider groups in society. Most urban workers are more concerned with the 11 percent inflation rate than such abstract issues as democracy. One poster urged the students to join in the planned march Wednesday to `` propagate among the masses the necessity of democracy and rule of law.'' Another claimed, `` A small breeze at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> can raise up a storm nationwide.'' One poster accused the government of paying more attention to crushing student protests than stamping out official corruption. `` Even a dog that is wronged gives a few barks. But we <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> students are n't even as good as a dog,'' it taunted, challeging students to speak out.
