grafs pvs to provide additional detail on launch. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Bulgarian cosmonaut rocketed into a clear blue sky today along with two Soviets in the first manned space mission of 1988, a launch televised live and featuring broadcasts from inside the capsule. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON>, 36, of the Bulgarian town of <LOCATION> Omurtag </LOCATION>, and the two Soviets blasted off at 6:03 p.m. -LRB- 10:03 a.m. EDT -RRB- aboard a Soyuz TM-5 capsule from the Baikonur Cosmodrome in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Soviet television gave unusually extensive coverage of the liftoff, showing live pictures of <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON>'s family in <LOCATION> Omurtag </LOCATION> and black-and-white shots of the cosmonauts in the moments before and after launch. `` I feel excellent,'' <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON> said on the live broadcast seconds after the launch. The broadcast, which lasted more than an hour, showed <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON>'s mother and other members of his family watching the launch on television in <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>'s defense minister was among the dignitaries viewing the liftoff at the Baikonur Cosmodrome in the republic of <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION>. The broadcast showed cheering, waving crowds gathered on Bulgarian streets. Only a few clouds were visible in television shots of Baikonur. Orange flames coming from the Vostok booster rocket contrasted with the blue sky in the background. The mission comes while the American manned space program is grounded. The last launch, in January 1986, ended in disaster. Seven astronauts were killed when the space shuttle Challenger exploded. <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON> and cosmonauts <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Savinykh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Y. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solovyov </PERSON> are scheduled to dock Thursday with the Soviet space station Mir. Already aboard Mir are cosmonauts <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Titov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Musa </PERSON> <PERSON> Manarov </PERSON>, who were the last men to enter space. They boarded Mir on Dec. 23, 1987. During a 10-day mission, <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON> and his four Soviet colleagues are to conduct about 40 experiments, some using Bulgarian equipment. The expermiments involve space physics, remote sensing of <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, space biology and medicine, the news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> has said. The cosmonauts are taking with them an orchid grown on Earth from seeds originally planted on the Mir station, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The last Bulgarian-Soviet flight, in April 1979, was marred by a failed attempt to dock with the Salyut space station. The Soviets plan several other manned missions this year, including crews from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.
