<HEAD>INF Verification Teams Meeting For First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A U.S.-Soviet commission verifying compliance with the Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces treaty signed by the two superpowers is meeting in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> today for the first time. Under the treaty, signed in December by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> must eliminate all missiles with ranges between 300 miles and 3,400 miles. The <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Verification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is to discuss any problems that may arise in verifying the elimination of an entire class of missiles. The treaty says that within 30 days `` after entry into force,'' each party must provide the other side with updated data on the number and location of its missiles. The treaty entered into force June 1, when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> exchanged the documents of ratification at their <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit. The treaty also says that either side can request a meeting of the commission to resolve questions relating to compliance with the accord or to `` agree on such measures as may be necessary to improve the viability and effectiveness'' of the treaty. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> side is headed by <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Steiner </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, and the Soviet side by <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Streltsov </PERSON>, who was a member of the INF treaty negotiating team. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said they anticipated that the session would last about two weeks.
