<HEAD>Navy Begins Eletromagnetic Pulsing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with tests started; picks up 6th
graf, `The barge ...' ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While environmentalists waited for a judge to consider their request to stop the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> from generating intense electromagnetic pulses off the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> coast, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> announced today that the tests had begun. The tests, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, are intended to measure the ability of naval equipment to withstand radiation following a nuclear blast. The Pentagon said the Empress II barge had reached the test site off the <LOCATION> Virginia-North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> coast Monday afternoon and began the monthlong experiment by transmitting three micro-second bursts of electrical energy at around 4 p.m. `` At about 8 a.m. this morning the generator began the second day of tests,'' said Lt. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kent </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The tests, she said, were being monitored by sophisticated measuring devices onshore, 15 miles away. `` The effect of the transmissions at those sites would be the same as sitting inside a car and transmitting on a <ORGANIZATION> CB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> for one second,'' she said. The Foundation on Economic Trends, a Washington-based environmental group, asked the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> on Monday to halt the project. `` Right now our attorneys are at the courthouse trying to get the judge to set a time for a hearing on our request for an injunction while we appeal the last court ruling,'' said <PERSON> Jeremy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON>, director of the foundation. The barge Empress II is designed to simulate the electromagnetic radiation that would follow the detonation of a nuclear weapon outside the Earth's atmosphere. The tests are intended to determine the ability of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships, aircraft and weapons to withstand the pulses. Empress II, or Electromagnetic Pulse Radiation Environment Simulator for Ships, Second Generation, can generate pulses of up to 7 million volts. Environmentalists have expressed concern the surges will disrupt the marine environment within the test area, and might affect computers and other delicate equipment outside it. `` We just do not believe the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has taken a hard look at these possible consequences at this particular site,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Kimbrell </PERSON>, an attorney for the foundation. The foundation filed a lawsuit in 1987 and reached agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> last month that an environmental impact statement was needed before testing could begin. The foundation's interpretation of the agreement was that the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> would submit an environmental impact statement on the site it chose for testing, which could take up to two years. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s interpretation was that it would submit an impact statement, but that the study would not necessarily involve a specific site. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> submitted a statement previously drawn up for a <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> site. A federal judge ruled Friday that the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s interpretation was plausible, and allowed the tests to proceed. Several calls today to the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> seeking to find out the time for the tests were not returned. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> insists that no dangers to the environment have been found in 20 years of similar testing and exhaustive studies.
