<HEAD>Hospital Chief: County President Knew About Experiments In January</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drug experiments on more than 200 pregnant women were known to the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, but he did not tell other commissioners, according to the director of the county hospital. Two doctors gave Dilantin, a drug commonly used to treat epilepsy, to about 245 pregnant women to determine whether the drug reduced fetal stress during Caesarean-section births, hospital Director <PERSON> Terrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said. But only five of the women had consented to participate in the hospital-approved study that began in September 1987, he said. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> and other hospital officials met with the board, which acts as trustees for the hospital, behind closed doors for nearly two hours Monday to discuss the case against the two anesthesiologists. Several board members said they were angry and shocked when they heard the disclosure. The board's president, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunne </PERSON>, said he did n't recall being told. He said the board would take no immediate action and would wait for the hospital medical staff's executive committee to finish its investigation, a process required under medical staff bylaws. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dunne </PERSON> was told about the experiments in January when hospital medical director Dr. <PERSON> Agnes </PERSON> <PERSON> Lattimer </PERSON> ordered a halt to the study. `` We told President <PERSON> Dunne </PERSON> and he advised us to follow due process according to the hospital's bylaws,'' <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Dunne </PERSON> said, `` I do n't recall that conversation.'' Commissioner <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Vaughan </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospitals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> which oversees <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Oak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Cermak </PERSON> hospitals, said, `` Doctors should know that you do n't conduct experiments on patients without getting their consent.'' <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said the doctors' study called for giving the drug to no more than 50 pregnant patients who were candidates for Caesarean-section deliveries. `` The great majority'' of the 245 patients given the drug were pregnant, <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said, adding that he knew `` at least one patient'' who was not. He said he was not sure why non-pregnant women would have been given Dilantin. Several past studies have reported higher incidences of birth defects, including heart abnormalities and retardation, in babies born to women who regularly used Dilantin and other drugs used to combat epileptic seizures. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> has noted, however, that the women at <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> were given a single dose of between 500 and 700 milligrams _ `` substantially lower'' than a normal dose _ at or near the time they delivered. Ms. <PERSON> Lattimer </PERSON> said she was convinced the pregnant women who had been given the drug without their consent suffered `` no adverse effects.'' `` That does not mean it is not a serious infraction and should not be prevented from happening again,'' she said. `` The physicians involved in this study violated hospital regulations.''
