<HEAD>Radicals Demanding Talks With North Korea Battle Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fierce fighting broke out at a <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> university Tuesday when masked students attacked riot police with rocks and firebombs and shouted anti-government and anti-U.S. slogans. Student leaders at other universities organized peaceful rallies and vowed to march to the border with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in an attempt to force reunification of the North and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>. `` Down with the military dictatorship!'' and `` Yankee go home!'' students at <ORGANIZATION> Soongshil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> yelled as they dashed out to hurl firebombs that exploded in flames around police in front of the school. The violence erupted during mourning for a student from the university who died Monday after setting himself afire during an anti-government protest. Police fired hundreds of rounds of tear gas but were forced back several times by groups of protesters who barricaded a road with two basketball backboards and wielded clubs under cover of firebombs and rocks flying from the rooftop of a school building. The fighting involved about 1,000 students and continued for several hours, often carrying into nearby alleys, as students chased squadrons of police huddling behind shields. Both students and policemen were seen being hit by rocks and other missiles, but police had no overall injury figures. The front of the campus was draped in black mourning banners as students inside the school stood watch over the coffin of Park Rae-chun. Park was the third student to commit suicide in a month. Violent clashes erupted at several provincial campuses, but students held peaceful rallies at many other schools across the country to prepare for a planned march Friday to the border truce village of <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION>. Despite repeated government warnings, radical student leaders vow to go ahead with their march to the border to force unification of the peninsula, divided in 1945 into Communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and pro-Western <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. `` Drive out <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION> who forced the partition of our land!'' a speaker shouted at a campus rally. Police vowed to arrest all students marching to the heavily militarized border. Opposition parties also opposed the march, urging students to leave contacts with the North to official channels. The protesters contend that the presence of 42,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> _ based here under a mutual defense pact _ hinders reunification of the two Koreas. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Defense Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said Tuesday that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops would stay in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> `` as long as the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> people want us to stay.'' `` The threat from the North has not abated, and the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> continue to modernize their armed forces and deploy them forward in a threatening manner,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said after arriving in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> and many other American officers are here for annual U.S.-South Korean security consultations, which will include <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> security help to ensure a successful Olympics. The Games begin Sept. 19 in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>.
