<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The White House AIDS commission opened debate today on its chairman's 579 proposed recommendations, amid indications there will be a lot of talk but little real controversy over most of them. `` There is no controversy in the first 11 chapters,'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> told fellow commissioners. Those chapters contain all of the recommendations _ except those calling for granting the surgeon general sweeping powers to deal with the epidemic. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> made clear to the panel chairman, retired <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Adm. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>, that he does not agree with his recommendations for essentially turning the AIDS fight over to Surgeon General <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Koop </PERSON>. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said he was determined that the commission make some recommendation to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on the best way to structure the federal health bureaucracy to deal with AIDS. `` It is not well done today,'' said <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>. Government bureaucracies usually work, except when they have to move quickly in emergencies, said <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>, a former member of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION>. And AIDS, he said, is a national health emergency. While saying he was not necessarily determined to stick to his recommendation that the surgeon general head the fight, <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said the commission has a responsibility to reach a consensus because `` we're in the best position to do it.'' A cornerstone of the recommendations <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> made last Thursday was a call for federal legislation to protect from discrimination people who have the AIDS virus. Although somewhat controversial because it runs counter to the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's stated position, there was clear consensus on the commission to retain that in the final report due at the White House June 24. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> expressed slight reservation about whether <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should be getting into that area, but made clear that he favors some kind of anti-discrimination protection. `` If we're going to make it, we should expand it to cover not just AIDS, but all diseases,'' he said. After brief opening remarks, the commission began a page-by-page discussion of the 269-page report. It plans at least two more days of meetings next Thursday and Friday to vote on the final version, running into the weekend if necessary to complete deliberations.
