<HEAD>Votes Switch Or Trade Bill Is Doomed, Senate Leaders Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Congressional efforts to make the omnibus trade bill law over President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto are doomed unless sponsors can switch a handful of votes before Wednesday's showdown on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor, leaders said Tuesday. `` I hope enough senators will change their minds tomorrow ... and override the president's veto,'' <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, told <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said he could not change the votes and could only hope that last-minute home-state pressure would cause three senators to relent and provide the two-thirds margin needed to override <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto of the 1,000-page bill, designed to strengthen the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> position in the international marketplace. Centerpiece provisions would overhaul the system under which the government imposes import curbs as a means of aiding <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industries and punishing international trade violations by other countries. A wide array of other provisions range from hefty agricultural subsidies to repeal of the 1980 windfall profits tax on oil-industry earnings. The president vetoed the bill May 24, focusing heavily on opposition to a provision that would require companies with 100 employees or more to provide notice to their workers of impending plant closings and large-scale layoffs. In short order, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted 308-113 to override the veto and approve the bill. But supporters of the measure have found the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> tougher going. `` We're winning,'' <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., a critic of the measure, told reporters `` We've got 36'' votes. Even if one senator, Democrat <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, were not at home recuperating from surgery, opponents would be able to put an override out of reach if they could muster 34 votes in the 100-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The administration has said it wants a more moderate version of the trade bill once the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> sustains the veto. There has been cloakroom talk that some senators looking at their re-election campaigns feel more comfortable about supporting the veto if they are assured that there will be another chance to vote on the trade issue before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adjourns in October. But it remains uncertain whether there will be such a second bill. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> has repeatedly raised the possibility that a raft of potential amendments that already have been taken care of over the last three years would reappear and stall the measure amid lengthy debate. `` There will have to be some agreement between the ledership and the committee to hold off amendments,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. He said there was scant precedent for such a procedure. Failure to approve a trade bill `` would be an issue'' in fall campaigns, `` but I do n't think an overriding issue,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` made a serious mistake on this veto'' because in disregarding the appeal of the plant-closings provision, `` the president has written off an issue that involves decency and right.'' `` The president was poorly advised on it,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said.
