<HEAD>Burning Tires Cause Environmental Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENUP, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Intake valves were ordered turned off from this northeastern <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> town's water supply source early Tuesday as sludge from an underground tire fire poured into the <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sandy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. The blaze, which started Monday and involved possibly 200,000 discarded auto tires in a dump the size of a football field, was producing a runoff of `` extremely contaminated and toxic oil,'' according to <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, a spokesman for the state Division of Disaster and <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. `` This has rather serious environmental implications because one tire can produce as much as three gallons of oil,'' <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> said. The owner of the property, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Blythe </PERSON>, and his family were evacuated, <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> said. He said <PERSON> Blythe </PERSON> owned a home, a hobby shop and a storage unit on the property. `` It does n't appear it -LRB- the fire -RRB- will be real easy to get put out, so we're looking at alternatives to decide which way to go,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burger </PERSON>, environmental response coordinator for the Natural Resources and <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Burger </PERSON> said two booms were placed across the river, and water company officials downstream were notified. Water intake valves on the river were shut off at 3 a.m., according to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinner </PERSON>, mayor of the town of 1,400 people. <PERSON> Greenup </PERSON> has just 38,000 gallons of reserve water for emergencies, <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kinner </PERSON> said residents have been asked to conserve, and tanker trucks may be brought in to supply