Sandinistas...'' SUBS 11th graf pvs ``Alfredo Cesar...'' to remove
redundant full first ference to Cesar. </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The leftist Sandinista government and rebel negotiators resumed talks today, and sources on both sides said they were close to agreeing on a definitive end to hostilities. As the talks began, <PERSON> Contra </PERSON> delegation leader <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> said: `` The Nicaraguan Resistance is here with a political decision to sign a definite agreement for permanent and lasting peace in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> if the government shows its political commitment to make the democratic reforms in this country to achieve that lasting peace.'' A major stumbling block in the fourth round of the negotiations on achieving a lasting peace is a timetable for disarming the U.S.-backed rebels, sources said Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> want the rebels, known as Contras, to disarm by September. The rebels want to do it by the end of January. At the last parley May 26-28, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> made concessions on what the rebels call the democratization of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and pledged to enact political reforms the Contras demand. But rebel representatives speaking privately to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> said the reforms remained too ill-defined. They include freedom of the press, lifting of all political restrictions, ending the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>'s control of the army and government, the right to strike and electoral reforms. The government also said it was willing to negotiate reforms within the framework of its dialogue with the internal opposition. The Contras reluctantly agreed at the last negotiating session to extend a 60-day cease-fire that would have expired May 31. But they said they would not observe the truce past the end of this week's talks The government had announced a unilateral 30-day extension of the truce. Since the talks last month, each side has accused the other of violating the truce. At least one Sandinista army soldier and 10 rebels have been killed, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> said Monday that the rebels were prepared to resume fighting if the talks failed. `` The Nicaraguan Resistance does not want to reinitiate the war, but if the Sandinista government suspends the conversations, our forces will be ready,'' <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>. The Resistance is the Contras' umbrella organization. On Monday night, Vice President <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> told reporters an accord with the rebels was `` a matter of moments because at best within a month they will not have the capacity to negotiate more.'' <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> also said negotiations only became possible because the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has been unable to win <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> support for continued military aid to the rebels. Despite their posturing, the government and rebels appear to be closer to a permanent agreement than at any time since they signed their historic peace outline on March 23 in the southern border town of <LOCATION> Sopoa </LOCATION>. The Sandinista government needs to end the war, now in its seventh year, to reconstruct an economy badly ravaged by the fighting that has claimed more than 26,000 lives and to enact the social programs it promised when it came to power in a 1979 revolution. At the same time, the Contras are experiencing deep divisions among their ranks and were cut off from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military assistance at the end of February.
