<FIRST>u w AM-Anti-GayViolence Bjt   06-07 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anti-Gay Violence, Bjt,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attacks On Homosexuals Up Sharply as AIDS Makes Gays More Visible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The AIDS epidemic has made <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s homosexual community more vulnerable to attack, according to a study released Tuesday that said reported incidents of anti-gay violence rose 42 percent last year. A record 7,008 incidents, ranging from verbal abuse to murder, were reported in 1987 to the National Gay and <ORGANIZATION> Lesbian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Berrill </PERSON>, director of the group's Anti-Violence Project. The statistics were included in the report `` Anti-Gay Violence, Victimization & amp; Defamation in 1987,'' the third such annual study by the gay-rights advocacy group. `` We are a community under siege,'' <PERSON> Berrill </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` We are battling AIDS and we're battling violence.'' AIDS _ acquired immune deficiency syndrome _ has made the gay community more visible, <PERSON> Berrill </PERSON> said, and `` the downside of lesbian and gay visibility is once you're more visible, you're more of a target.'' Fifteen percent of all incidents reported last year and 5 percent of the physical assaults involved verbal reference to AIDS by the perpetrators or were directed against people with the disease, the study found. As in 1986, nearly two-thirds of the local groups reporting anti-gay incidents last year believed that `` fear and hatred associated with AIDS has fostered anti-gay violence in their communities,'' according to the report. The overall statistics represented a small percentage of the actual number of anti-gay incidents occurring last year, <PERSON> Berrill </PERSON> said. `` Gay and lesbian victims are probably the least likely to report of any hate crime victims,'' he said. `` Gay and lesbian people, by reporting crimes against them to the police, risk losing their jobs, their homes, and in some cases children.'' Nevertheless, `` available data clearly demonstrate that the problem continues to be severe,'' he said. <PERSON> Berrill </PERSON> called for federal and state legislation aimed at curbing anti-gay violence and better education of the public. Another reason for the increase in incidents reported may have been that the task force received more complete data than in the prior studies, <PERSON> Berrill </PERSON> noted. The 7,008 incidents in 1987 were reported by 64 groups in 32 states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, compared with 4,946 incidents from 41 groups in 27 states a year earlier. The report was compiled by sending one-page questionnaires to more than 150 groups in all 50 states requesting any available local data on harassment or violence that occurred in 1987. Groups were chosen based on the likelihood of knowledge about local incidents. Among those groups documenting greater violence last year were <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Violence </ORGANIZATION>, a gay victim-assistance agency, which saw 11 percent more violence victims in 1987 than in 1986. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> Gay and Lesbian Anti-Violence Project said it served 14 percent more clients in 1987, and the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lesbian </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Gay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> reported a 39 percent increase in violent incidents. The greatest increases came in acts of verbal harassment and threats of violence, according to the report. `` Not only were there 1,990 more such incidents reported in 1987 than the previous year, but harassment and threats also constituted a greater percentage of 1987's total -LRB- 78 percent of all episodes in 1987 as compared to 70 percent in 1986 -RRB-,'' it said. Acts of vandalism also increased: 338 in 1987, up from 191 in 1986. While 835 physical assaults were reported in 1987, compared with 732 in 1986, they represented a slightly smaller percentage of total incidents: 12 percent in 1987, down from 15 percent in 1986. Reports of police-related incidents declined from 410 to 217. Other declines were in reports of arson, bombings, bomb threats and homicides. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> had more reported incidents than any other state _ a total of 1,985, of which 1,913 were harassment or threats, the report found. <PERSON> Berrill </PERSON> attributed this to the fact that organized hate groups are active in the state. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state led all others in the number of anti-gay homicides, the report found. Of a total of 408 incidents reported in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, 20 were homicides. Sixty-four murders were reported nationwide. The study also highlighted federal, state and local initiatives to combat such violence, including passage of a hate crimes statistics bill by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> last month. The bill would require federal collection of statistics on crimes motivated by race, religion, sexual orientation or ethnicity. A companion bill has been introduced in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif.
</TEXT>
