 The final round of the primary season was considerably less than an all-out struggle. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spent less than $ 250,000 on television in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and nothing on TV advertising in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s campaign said it was spending $ 700,000 in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, but even that was a relative pittance in the state with the most delegates of all. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, trying to avoid overshooting federal spending limitations, had no commercials and little organizational effort. His <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> office had one paid staff member and a handful of telephone lines. All this was in astonishing contrast to the primaries and caucuses at the beginning of the campaign season, when <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and their rivals of long ago lavished time and money on states such as <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>. It was a marked contrast, as well, to <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> and Democratic campaigns of the past, when the outcome of nominating struggles hung in the balance to be tipped one way or another by the voters of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. And even as one primary season was ending, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was debating whether to make changes in the next one. A <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee heard testimony during the day on legislation to establish a regional primary system, with the states clustered into half a dozen geographical categories. Thus ended a primary season that began with the clamor of more than a dozen candidates but sorted out quickly. That was true particularly on the Republican side, where <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made short work of his five rivals even though he was very nearly an ear