ch as <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' route to the nomination mirrored the man _ steady and methodical. He finished third in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, as did <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, then rebounded to capture a back-yard victory in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>. His Super Tuesday was considerably less so than the vice president's, but super enough. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> managed to pull out Southern victories in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> with less than half the vote. He won at home in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> the same day. But he stumbled the next time out, finishing third in the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> primary and was embarrassed a few days later when <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> trounced him in the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> caucuses. That was the end of his primary disappointments. He then began a springtime surge through the primaries that forced all his rivals but <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> from the field _ and left little or no doubt that he would be the nominee. Leading to the final week of the campaign, he won nine of the last 10 primaries, often by landslide margins over his sole remaining rival, and gradually built his delegate totals toward the nomination.
