<HEAD>Official Says Starvation Kills Almost 1,000 in Southern Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Almost 1,000 people have died of starvation in a parched southern town that has n't received relief food for about a year, and most of the deaths occurred in recent weeks, a Sudanese official said Tuesday. Sultan Pio Tem, commissioner of the eastern part of <LOCATION> Bahr </LOCATION> <LOCATION> el-Ghazal </LOCATION> region, told reporters the victims were residents of <LOCATION> Aweil </LOCATION>, northwest of the regional capital <LOCATION> Wau </LOCATION>. He said the victims also included people forced into the town by fierce fighting in the 5-year-old civil war. The rebel <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> holds 90 percent of the countryside in the south. The government retains control of the large towns and cities, and many peasants have fled to them seeking army protection. Tem said the latest telegram he received from <LOCATION> Aweil </LOCATION> reported 786 people had died from hunger and hunger-related diseases from May 24 to June 1. He said 210 others perished earlier from the same causes and that starvation deaths continue to occur there daily. He did not say how many were dying each day. Tem was in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> seeking relief food for the town. He said he was to meet with <PERSON> Darios </PERSON> <PERSON> Beshir </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bahr </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Ghazal </PERSON>'s regional govenor. Tem said relief supplies had not reached <LOCATION> Aweil </LOCATION> since a consignment of rice and edible oil arrived by train a year ago. Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Mahdi </PERSON> has not replied to an appeal for food and medicine addressed to the government and to Western relief organizations, <PERSON> Tem </PERSON> said, adding he was trying to meet with <PERSON> el-Mahdi </PERSON> to urge him to declare <LOCATION> Aweil </LOCATION> a hunger area. <PERSON> El-Mahdi </PERSON> has announced that the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> is sponsoring a program to transport relief food to the south, but no date has been set for the operation. The <ORGANIZATION> SPLA </ORGANIZATION> took up arms against the government in 1983 to demand more autonomy and administrative and economic reforms. The years of fighting have corresponded with one of the worst famines in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> in years.
