<HEAD>Mondale Urges Campaign Changes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primaries Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Vice President <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> on Tuesday urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to order a system of regional presidential primaries to replace a hodgepodge that `` cries out for reform.'' <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>, who won the Democratic presidential nomination in 1984 but lost the general election to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, testified in support of a bill that would require such regional primaries, with the dates to be decided by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. It would also outlaw inter-party crossover voting in primaries. The measure is sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, D-Ill., though he told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> that the bill `` is not my brainchild. He noted that similar legislation was introduced by then-Sen. Mondale of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> in 1974 Mondale, testifying on the final day of the 1988 campaign season, said the present nominating system `` is the hodgepodge result of a decades-long accretion of rules and amendments by the conventions and national committees of the two political parties.'' He said primaries in widely scattered parts of the nation on the same day, such as Tuesday's schedule of contests in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, make it impossible for candidates to address the issues and meet the voters. He urged the panel to support the bill, which would allow states to decide on a caucus or primary form of election but would require them to hold the event on a specific date, based on their region. The six regional primaries, according to the bill, would begin on the last Tuesday in March and end on the second Tuesday in June. The <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> would decide the order, by lots, each year. <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>, drawing on his own experience, also criticized the influence of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, which hold the first-in-the-nation caucus and primary, respectively. In comments to reporters after his testimony, he said, `` I lived in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> for three years virtually. I could have gotten elected mayor in most of those towns, the same in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>.'' `` My theory is we ought to rotate those states so you do that in other states. We never had a Southern state, a Western state. If we're going to do that, let's circulate it.'' <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> said the present system is `` not all bad by any means,'' but `` nevertheless cries out for reform.'' He called on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to act now rather than drop the issue until the next presidential-election year.
