<HEAD>Bush Struggles to Define Race; Dukakis Benefits From Long Primary
Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The presidential primary season was kind to Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> but disquieting to Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who struggles to define the race in his terms despite clinching the nomination two months ago. The primary election results and the current polls could be likened to the electorate's first impressions of the candidates, impressions likely to change as they get to know the contenders better in the fall. Right now, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is riding a wave of public desire for change. After nearly eight years of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, the public may be looking for something different, a change of direction. Democratic and Republican pollsters alike report Americans are uneasy with the economy and concerned that the country is headed in the wrong direction. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is suffering from an inability to define the race in his terms. Peace and prosperity is a theme that has worked well for Republicans in the past, but, so far, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has n't been able to convince voters that it applies today. `` I ca n't wait for this primary season to end,'' the vice president tells rallies. From the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> viewpoint, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has had the best of all worlds the past three months. The contest for the Republican presidential nomination effectively ended on March 8, Super Tuesday, when <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> swept 16 primaries and sent Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> staggering back to the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> in search of a miracle. Any lingering doubts about the outcome ended a week later with another <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> landslide in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>; he mathematically locked up the nomination in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> on April 26. The GOP race was over, a footnote to news accounts of the struggle among the Democr