SON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> concedes that the vice president could be trailing by as much as 20 points in surveys before the Republican convention in August. But before <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> can send out invitations to his inauguration, he has some problems to resolve. The biggest one is <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. The former civil rights leader has a hold on the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s most loyal constituency and many of his followers think <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> must be offered the vice presidential nomination _ an offer <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is n't likely to make unless he is certain it would be turned down. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> also is threatening to wage convention fights for platform planks he favors. There are no foreseeable conflicts for the GOP convention, allowing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to gain maximum benefits from the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> coronation. And as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> reads the current polls showing him trailing <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, he also can take comfort in the fact that when voters start focusing on presidential campaigns in the fall, the race inevitably tightens, often dramatically.
</TEXT>
