<HEAD>Japan Most Often On Governors' Overseas Itineraries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When governors pack their bags and passports, where do they go? In 1987, they headed most often to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, according to a survey by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. It said governors from 43 states and territories made 87 overseas trips during 1987, often stopping in more than one country. But the most frequent destination was <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> -LRB- 36 trips -RRB-, followed by <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> -LRB- 19 -RRB-, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> -LRB- both 17 -RRB-, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> -LRB- 13 -RRB-, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> -LRB- both 9 -RRB-, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> -LRB- all 6 -RRB-, and <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> -LRB- all 3 -RRB-. <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> were each visited twice. Countries that drew a single governor were: <LOCATION> Anguilla </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saipan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lucia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Samoa </LOCATION>. The association said governors usually go abroad to encourage <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports, increase foreign investment and promote tourism. The 87 trips was nearly double the 45 overseas trips governors made in 1986. `` Nowadays, most governors are making one to five overseas trips a year to sell their states' resources, goods and services,'' according to an article in the Governors' Weekly Bulletin.
