<HEAD>Pepper Rallies His Forces for Floor Fight on Long-Term Care Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON> marshaled an array of influential lawmakers Tuesday as he prepared for a do-or-die effort in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to pass a costly new home health care program. Pepper's plan, scheduled for floor action Wednesday, would expand Medicare to include long-term home care benefits for anyone of any age who is chronically ill or ca n't perform tasks of daily living. With opponents mobilizing to prevent a vote on the bill, Pepper rallied his own forces Tuesday at a news conference: Sens. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>; Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> sponsor of the bill; and Reps. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mo </LOCATION>., who holds 4 leadership position in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>; and <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> health subcommittee `` We have a total vacuum'' when it comes to long-term care,'' Pepper, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., said `` A million people a year become destitute trying to pay for catastrophic care.'' The Pepper bill has provoked criticism on several counts, among them its high cost, its lack of a nursing home component and the unorthodox manner in which it bypassed committee scrutiny and sped to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. `` We should not allow the rules of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to be manipulated to satisfy the popular issue of the moment,'' <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., said Tuesday in a letter to his colleagues He said the committee system `` protects members from being forced to vote on popular-appearing proposals that may ultimately prove to be embarrassing.'' The Pepper bill is putting <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members, particularly Democrats, in a bind because withiout their support there is no chance <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will pass the bill before adjourning this year. There is overwhelming public sentiment in favor of a long-term care program. There also is an election in six months, and the 87-year-old Pepper, who is popular with elderly voters, has made campaign appearances on behalf of many lawmakers in the past. The <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> estimates the home care program would cost nearly $ 28 billion over five years. It would be paid for by imposing the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> payroll tax on income above $ 45,000, which is currently exempt. Supporters of the plan also backed a new catastrophic care benefit bill to help the elderly cope with acute illness. That Medicare expansion, more than a year in the making, has passed the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and is expected to pass the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> this week. But <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> called that measure `` only half the roof that people need to shield them from health care catastrophes. ... I always feel guilty calling this other bill the catastrophic bill.'' Pepper initially tried to attach his plan to the catastrophic bill, but withdrew it when lawmakers said it would sink that legislation. In return, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, agreed to let Pepper have a separate floor vote on his plan. Pepper, chairman of the rules committee that schedules floor action, scheduled his own bill last year, effectively bypassing <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>'s committee and the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> headed by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., which ordinarily would have considered the Pepper bill <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> complained in his `` Dear Colleague'' letter that the bill was brought to the floor via `` an extremely unusual and troubling procedure.'' He also said the agencies necessary to administer the Pepper plan do not exist and `` history has demonstrated that such a big program can not be put in place quickly without encouraging inept or fraudulent management.'' And he said <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION> estimates show the program would face an annual deficit within five years. Pepper dismissed the notion that he was abusing the committee process, saying what happened with his bill was unique and would not become routine. `` The rules committee is not going to run rampant over anybody,'' <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` All they want to do is kill the bill and use the money for something else.'' In a `` Dear Colleague'' letter of their own, dated June 8, Pepper and his co-sponsor, Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Roybal </PERSON>, D-Calif., called cost and procedure issues `` bogus'' reasons to oppose the bill They said the bill contains a cap on costs and does not violate any procedural rules of the House. They also said outside opposition groups such as the insurance industry would oppose any long-term care bill because `` they serve their own narrow self-interest, not the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people's interest.''
