<HEAD>With AM-Math Assessment Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: The correct, to CORRECT spelling of
`foreword'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Question: Is 26.9 percent `` fully a third''? The correct answer is no, but 26.9 percent is described as equaling a third in a foreword to the federal mathematics study released Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Anrig </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Testing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which runs the government-sponsored testing program, wrote in a preface that, `` Fully a third of our 13-year-olds have n't mastered skills universally taught in elementary school.'' The executive summary of the report also said it was `` alarming that one-third of these students'' did n't score 250 on the 500-point test, a level indicating they can perform basic operations and begin to solve problems. But a chart accompanying the test indicated that in 1986, 73.1 percent of the 13-year-olds actually reached that level, up from 64.9 percent in 1978. The full text of the report, `` The Mathematics Report Card: Are We Measuring Up,'' referring to the same statistics, says: `` It is alarming that one-quarter of the seventh and eighth graders _ amounting to more than three-quarters of a million students _ may not possess the skills ... necessary to perform many everyday tasks.'' <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashworth </PERSON>, a spokesman for the National Assessment, acknowledged that `` fully a third'' was a mistake, and expressed surprise that it had gotten past the report's proofreaders.
