<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A French editor paid a record $ 1 million for the rights to publish the French version of the sequel to the American classic `` Gone With the Wind,'' the editing company said Tuesday. <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Belfond </PERSON> of Editions <PERSON> Belfond </PERSON> said it was the largest sum ever paid for translation rights by a French publisher. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Books </ORGANIZATION> is paying novelist <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Ripley </PERSON> nearly $ 5 million to write the sequel to <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s only novel The sequel, which has yet to be named, is to be released in 1990, said <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Theresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiltz </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The French firm outbid six others in an auction last week to acquire the rights from the <ORGANIZATION> William </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, which controls overseas rights to the book, <PERSON> Belfond </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s novel, enormously successful when it was published in 1936, was the basis for the film classic starring <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Gable </PERSON> as <PERSON> Rhett </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> and <PERSON> Vivien </PERSON> <PERSON> Leigh </PERSON> as <PERSON> Scarlett </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Hara </PERSON>. <PERSON> Belfond </PERSON> has published translations of other best-selling American novels, including <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Susann </PERSON>'s `` Valley of the Dolls.'' French publisher <PERSON> Gallimard </PERSON>, which raked in millions with the translation of `` Autant en Emporte le Vent'' -LRB- `` Gone With the Wind'' -RRB- when it was published here in 1939, did not take part in negotiations for the sequel. A Gallimard spokesman said $ 1 million was `` an exhorbitant amount to pay for a doubtful return.'' <PERSON> Belfond </PERSON> acknowledged the purchase was a gamble. The French edition is expected to be on bookstore shelves by the end of 1990.
