<HEAD>Legislation Seeks Tighter Regulation of Medical Labs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Medical testing labs would come under strict federal regulation under a bill introduced Tuesday by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, D-Mich., and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Maine </LOCATION> The bill would affect the 80,000 to 100,000 medical laboratories not now under federal regulation. Most are in doctors' offices, <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said. `` Our legislation changes the focus of lab testing to emphasize quality over quantity,'' said <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>. `` That difference can have life-or-death consequences.'' The legislation would establish maximum workload limits for lab workers who examine Pap smears, strengthen federal enforcement authority over labs and set standards for the laboratories. `` From the patient's point of view, there should be just as much assurance that tests conducted in a doctor's office are as accurate'' as those conducted in a hospital or commercial lab, <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said.
