<FIRST>r w AM-FuelEconomy     06-07 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fuel Economy,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Appeals Court Upholds Agency's Lowering of CAFE Standard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> acted reasonably in lowering mandatory fuel economy standards to 26 miles per gallon, a federal appeals court ruled, 2-1, Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> lowered the corporate average fuel economy, or CAFE, standard automakers must meet in 1986 from the 27.5 mpg set by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to 26 mpg, asserting the higher standard was not economically practical. The state of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, the cities of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and four citizens groups, led by Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION>, filed petitions requesting a court review of the order. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION>, in an opinion by Judge <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Ginsburg </PERSON>, said <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION>'s `` consideration of the likelihood of economic hardship within its assessment of ` economic practicability' must be given due weight.'' The agency's decision was based on analysis that concluded the higher standard would have severe economic effects throughout the auto industry, and therefore was not arbitrary or capricious as the petitioners had charged, the court said. The petitioners also asserted that <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION>, by lowering the standard, had failed to consider the nation's need to conserve energy. The CAFE standards were initially adopted in the 1970s to reduce <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dependence on foreign oil. The court, however, said the agency had weighed increased fuel consumption against economic harm under broad guidelines set by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` Had <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> offered a more precise balancing formula for the agency to apply, ... we could more confidently discern the agency's compliance with the congressional mandate,'' the court said In the absence of such precision, the court said it must conclude <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> had properly accomodated conflicting policies in lowering the standard. Mrs. <PERSON> Ginsbug </PERSON> was joined in the majority by Judge <PERSON> Abner </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikva </PERSON>. Judge <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Silberman </PERSON> dissented. Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> has called for repeal of the CAFE standards, saying in an era of cheaper energy they have outlived their usefulness and harm the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> auto industry's competitiveness Supporters of the standards argue they must be retained to keep the nation from again slipping into deep dependence on unreliable foreign sources of oil. Besides <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION>, the petitions named <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Importers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> as defendants.
</TEXT>
