<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh-Islam     06-07 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh-Islam,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bangladesh Declares Islam State Religion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> passed a constitutional amendment Tuesday making Islam the state religion. Thousands of opponents took to the streets in protest, blocking traffic and damaging vehicles. The 300-member <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, dominated by President <PERSON> Hussain </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Jatiya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, passed the controversial bill 254-0. Fifteen members of minor opposition parties walked out before the vote. Two independents joined the <ORGANIZATION> Jatiya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to enact the bill, which was proposed May 11. The amendment makes an Islamic republic out of this once-secular state created after a 1971 war of independence from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Shortly after the legislation was passed, several thousand members of 21 non-voting opposition groups streamed into the streets. These parties have no representatives in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> because they boycotted March elections in which <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> won a 252-seat parliamentary majority. Witnesses said the mobs stopped traffic at several intersections in downtown <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> and damaged seven state-run buses and a police jeep. Riot police were on duty, but no clashes were reported. The proposed bill drew especially strong criticism from women's groups, opposition parties and minority religions in a country whose 105 million people are 85 percent Moslem There are an estimated 250,000 Christians in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, as well as Hindu and <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> minorities. The bill amends the <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> Constitution to insert the sentence: `` The religion of the republic is Islam, but other religions may be practiced in peace and harmony.'' The government says the bill does not change the legal system to one that would follow the Koran, the Moslem holy book. Women's rights groups, however, fear that Moslem fundamentalists may use the amendment to pressure the state to pass more rigid laws following Islamic traditions, such as those requiring women to hide their faces behind veils. But observers say there is little possibility that the amendment would pull <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> into a social system resembling the Islamic fundamentalism of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. About 3,000 demonstrators _ including teachers, journalists and doctors _ marched through the streets of <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> on Saturday to protest the change, shouting anti-government slogans. Christian leaders had appealed to <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> to withdraw the legislation. Among those who signed the statement was the Rev. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Rozario </PERSON>, the Roman Catholic archibishop of <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>, and representatives of other Christian denominations. Before the legislation was passed, Prime Minister <PERSON> Maudud </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> assured minority groups that they should not fear the amendment and told the <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> that the bill was `` to free Islam from the hands of fundamentalists and the traders of religion.'' But political analysts in <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> have said they believe <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON>'s main reason for launching Islam as the official religion was to woo Islamic fundamentalists, some of whom are campaigning against his regime for being too lax in supporting Moslem traditions <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON>, a former army general, came to power in a bloodless coup in March 1982 and was elected president in October 1986. The major opposition groups contend the elections were rigged. They boycotted the March elections, saying they also would be rigged, and vowed not to participate in elections until <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> leaves office.
</TEXT>
