<HEAD>CLU To Defend Child's Right To Be Educated Without Medication</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA ENGLERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it will help with an appeal on behalf of a 9-year-old boy and his parents, who refuse to medicate him to control his hyperactivity in school. The group agreed to assist <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> <PERSON> Jesson </PERSON>'s lawyer in appealing a state hearing officer's decision that the boy must take Ritalin or an alternative drug to calm hyperactive children if he continues to attend regular public school classes next year. School officials in <LOCATION> Derry </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> was manageable on Ritalin and that without it he has temper tantrums and is disruptive. His parents, <PERSON> Valerie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Ritalin </PERSON> made <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> act like a drug addict with facial twitches, little appetite and insomnia. They stopped giving him Ritalin in April 1987 after he spent 18 months on the drug. The appeal likely will be filed in federal court, where precedent exists for such matters, <PERSON> Claire </PERSON> <PERSON> Ebel </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> CLU </ORGANIZATION>'s executive director, said Tuesday. The first line of defense will be to assert <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>'s constitutional right to privacy when medical treatment is involved, she said `` For any government agency, such as the state <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, to violate that privacy, there must exist a compelling state interest and we do n't believe that has been proven,'' she said. The group's lawyers also believe <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>'s rights as an educationally handicapped child have been violated, <PERSON> Ebel </PERSON> said. Hearing officer <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Falkenham </PERSON> ruled last month that returning <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> to class without medication would harm his education and that of his classmates. <PERSON> Falkehham </PERSON> also said the <PERSON> Jessons </PERSON> would have to pay to have <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> placed in a more restrictive, specialized class if they refuse to medicate him. In an agreement between the state and <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>'s parents, he is being tutored until the school year ends later this month.
