<HEAD>Drought Drying Up Water Supplies, Patience Of Residents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The drought that has gripped north <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> is causing a new kind of battle among lawn-conscious suburbanites, some of whom are reporting their neighbors for ignoring tight restrictions on outdoor water use. <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has been swamped with water calls, said operator <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, who estimated that 90 percent of the department's recent calls have been about outdoor watering. `` They say, ` Their lawn's so pretty and green, how come they get to water and I do n't,''' she said. `` They're calling in on their neighbors, basically,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Cobb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> radio operator <PERSON> Nina </PERSON> <PERSON> Reber </PERSON>. `` Some are pretty mad,'' said <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>, deputy director of <LOCATION> DeKalb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` Some just want to complain. Lots are just teed off at their neighbors.'' <ORGANIZATION> Gwinnett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Beaufait </PERSON> said his department received nearly 230 calls over the weekend. `` When a resident sees somebody else watering, I would imagine he would be irritated,'' <PERSON> Beaufait </PERSON> said. Almost every government in the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> area has restrictions on when lawns can be watered and cars washed. The city of <LOCATION> Roswell </LOCATION>, in northern <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, announced that it would ban outdoor watering 24 hours a day beginning at midnight Tuesday. <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> has banned outdoor watering from 7 a.m. to 11 a.m. since November, and its water bureau is recommending that residents use water outdoors on odd or even days, depending on their address. Despite the bans, faucets in about 1,000 north <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> homes went dry from about 9 p.m. Monday until 1 a.m. Tuesday, said county water supervisor <PERSON> Hershel </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrett </PERSON>. He said the area, which bans outdoor watering from noon until 9 p.m., ran out of water because many residents `` just dragged out the water hoses and went to town'' when the ban expired Monday night. `` We were, for all practical purposes, out of water last night,'' he said Tuesday. About 200 homes in southern <LOCATION> Forsyth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, where water was purchased from <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, also lost water for three to four hours Monday night, said <PERSON> Forsyth </PERSON> water department director <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Heard </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> state climatologist <PERSON> Gayther </PERSON> <PERSON> Plummer </PERSON> said there have been only 210 inches of rain in most parts of north <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> in the last five years. The region averages 50 inches of rainfall per year, or 250 inches in five years. <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON>, the metropolitan area's primary water source, was at 1,062.7 feet above sea level Tuesday, 10 feet above its record low of 1,052.7 feet, set Dec. 24, 1981. `` All indications are that this is going to be a very critical drought in the northern part of the state,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Word </PERSON>, chief of water resource management for the <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is going to be worse than'86.'' However, <PERSON> Word </PERSON> said the driest weather this year is confined to north <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, unlike the statewide drought in 1986. The water situation in the <LOCATION> northeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Clayton </LOCATION> _ which was without water for 36 hours during the summer of 1986 _ will be critical if the town does n't receive significant rainfall soon, Mayor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramey </PERSON> said Tuesday. But <PERSON> Ramey </PERSON> said the experience of running out of water taught residents the importance of conservation. `` It was a lesson well learned, because when they turned that tap on and nothing came out they knew we were n't fooling,'' he said.
