<HEAD>Sequoyah Unit 2 Shuts Down Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Unit 2 reactor at <ORGANIZATION> Sequoyah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> automatically shut down Monday afternoon for the third time since it was restarted last month, said a <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Authority </LOCATION> official. The reason for the 2:15 p.m. EDT shutdown was not immediately known, said <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for Plant Manager <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. It occurred less than a week after the reactor reached 100 percent power for the first time since it was restarted following a 33-month shutdown. <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> brought Unit 2 back on line May 13, the agency's first reactor to be restarted since its nuclear system was shut down in August 1985 to correct safety and management problems. Although two automatic shutdowns delayed the restart process, Unit 2 at the plant outside <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION> reached full generating capacity May 31. <ORGANIZATION> Sequoyah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION> 2 began commercial operation in June 1982; the following year, it set a <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> record by operating 195 consecutive days without a shutdown. That record was later broken by a 197-day streak by Unit 1 in 1984 and 1985. <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> tentatively plans to restart <ORGANIZATION> Sequoyah </ORGANIZATION> Unit 1 in August or September, with Unit 2 at the three-reactor <ORGANIZATION> Browns </ORGANIZATION> Ferry Nuclear Plant near <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, to follow by the end of the year.
