<HEAD>Growth of Consumer Credit Slowed in April</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans increased their installment borrowing at a moderate annual rate of 7 percent in April as growth in consumer credit slowed from the first three months of the year, the government said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said consumers took out $ 3.65 billion more in credit than they paid off in April, compared with net growth of $ 5.2 billion in March, $ 5.0 billion in February and $ 6.2 billion in January. The annual rate of growth in April was slightly slower than the 7.2 percent rate for all of 1987 and considerably slower than the approximately 10.7 percent pace for the first quarter of 1988. However, economists saw the slowing as a healthy trend at a time when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers are trying to boost their production for export. `` What's happened is what should be happening. Consumer spending is cooling off and freeing up resources to produce for export,'' said <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaber </PERSON>, an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> consulting firm. `` The whole transition from a consumer-led economy to an export-led economy assumes we can cool off consumer demand in order to avoid heated up inflation,'' she said. She said consumer debt grew faster than the norm in the January-March period because of a surge in auto sales. In April, auto loans grew by $ 1.55 billion, a yearly growth rate of 6.7 percent, compared with a rate of 15.9 percent in March and 14.5 percent in February. The category that includes credit card debt showed the strongest increase in April _ $ 1.61 billion for an 11.7 percent expansion pace, compared with 16 percent in March and 10.3 percent in February. The credit report said the category that includes bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate increased by $ 478 million in April, a 3.6 percent jump compared with a 3.7 percent decline a month earlier. Borrowing for mobile homes increased by $ 13 million, 0.6 percent, after a drop of 5.8 percent in March. The various changes left total consumer debt at $ 633.1 billion at the end of April, up 9.1 percent from a year earlier. Still, Ms. <PERSON> Shaber </PERSON> said consumer borrowing as a percentage of income has remained steady at just under 19 percent for a year and a half.
