<TEXT>
 The first Indian soldiers were withdrawn from <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> on Tuesday since <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> sent more than 50,000 peacekeeping troops to the island 10 months ago. About 400 soldiers sat cross-legged on a dock in this port city waiting to sail home to <LOCATION> Madras </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. Indian officials had said earlier that as many as 3,000 Indian soldiers would be withdrawn this week. But, citing security reasons, they declined Tuesday to give specific figures. Indian army musicians played martial music on bagpipes as about a dozen armored personnel carriers and several jeeps and trucks were hoisted aboard an Indian freighter. `` Do not call this a withdrawal, but a thinning out of troops,'' said Sri Lankan Gen. <PERSON> Sepala </PERSON> <PERSON> Attygalle </PERSON>, who attended the ceremony in <LOCATION> Trincomalee </LOCATION>, 150 miles northeast of the capital of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. The Indians first began arriving on July 30, a day after <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> signed an Indian-brokered peace accord aimed at ending the civil war in the northeast of the island between Tamil rebels and the Sinhalese Buddhists. Many among the Sinhalese have opposed the presence of the Indian troops, who they fear may stay on the island. `` This is the beginning of the end of suspicions and apprehensions about <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s intentions on <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>,'' said Indian High Commissioner J.N. <PERSON> Dixit </PERSON> _ the equivalent of ambassador _ who spoke to a news conference in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> after the ceremony. Lt. Gen. <PERSON> A.S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalkat </PERSON>, the Indian commanding officer in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> lanka </LOCATION>, praised his departing men for their sacrifice in helping <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> 