n a domestic dispute, the injured party may sign a criminal complaint and a court date will be set. If the crime is a misdemeanor, the defendant is held until posting bond; if it is a felony, a state's attorney is summoned to interview the complainant, witnesses and the accused, and decide whether to file charges. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, 55, was in fair condition Tuesday with two gunshot wounds in the head and four in the neck, said hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Rea </PERSON>. Police records show that <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> has received psychiatric treatment and has been on disability leave because of emotional problems, <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Vicini </PERSON> confirmed that <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> has been on disability but said she did n't know why. `` The shooting was caused, I believe, by a battered-son syndrome,'' <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> said. `` The father would beat up the mother, and the son, who was the oldest of their four children, would intercede on behalf of the mother. `` The father would taunt him and say he was the mother's bodyguard and then beat the son. During a bond hearing Monday for the younger <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> filed a motion in <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> with examples of the alleged abuse by the elder <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, a 32-year veteran of the department. After listening to the allegations, Associate Circuit Judge <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolan </PERSON> reduced the son's bond from $ 500,000 to $ 10,000 and called the elder <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> `` an absolute menace to his immediate family.'' `` He's a time bomb who goes off and repeatedly goes off,'' the judge said. In the most recent incident, <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> said <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> threatened to kill his wife May 24 with a pistol and then chased his son around the yard, threatening to kill him, after he tried to help his mother. Police took the elder <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>'s gun but did n't arrest him because they considered it a domestic dispute, <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> said. `` When a policeman is called to the home of a fellow officer, he treats him as a fellow officer and he treats everyone else as an outsider,'' <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> said. `` So if the officer is accused, they listen to him instead of the person making the complaint.''
