background on election. Picks up 4th pvs, `Rafsanjani, 53...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s parliament re-elected <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> as its speaker on Tuesday, cementing his political and military power. Parliament voted in a firebrand cleric as <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s deputy. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s re-election to the key position came only five days after <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> named him commander-in-chief of the country's armed forces. That appointment followed two serious military defeats for <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in the nearly 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, reported that 187 of the 192 parliamentary deputies whose credentials had been approved since elections in April and May voted for <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>. Five abstained. Radicals, many of them <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> supporters, made sweeping gains in the elections at the expense of conservatives who have blocked economic reforms. The elction sharpened divisions between radicals, who seek a centralized state-run economy, and the conservatives, who are backed by the `` Bazaaris,'' the wealthy merchant class. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, 53, was named temporary speaker when the parliament, or Majlis, convened May 28, pending a two-thirds quorum to elect a permanent speaker. He has been speaker since 1980. The Majlis also elected two deputy speakers Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION> reported. One is <PERSON> Hojatoleslam </PERSON> <PERSON> Mehdi </PERSON> <PERSON> Karroubi </PERSON>, a middle-ranking cleric who is the militant head of the <ORGANIZATION> Pilgrimage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> and believed to have been responsible for masterminding riots by Iranian pilgrims in the Holy Moslem city of <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> last year. Hundreds of people died in the riots. The other is <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Hashemian </PERSON>, a little-known deputy from <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s hometown of <LOCATION> Rafsanjan </LOCATION> in southeast <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s re-election appeared to set the seal on his political power. He is already <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s representative on the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which determines <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s strategy in the war. He sits on the Council for the Expediency of State Decrees, formed earlier this year by <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> to push radical economic reforms through parliament. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> also has strong links with the <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, which is now more powerful than the Iranian army, and leader of the clerics who deliver sermons at the weekly Friday prayer sessions in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, an influential religious and political platform. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s widening power leaves him well-placed to become the kingmaker in the power struggle among <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s fractious leadership that is expected to swell when <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> dies. The 87-year-old revolutionary patriarch has been reported in poor health. Speculation that his condition was deteriorating was heightened when he relinquished his constitutional position as commander-in-chief to <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, a middle-ranking cleric. There has been no hard evidence to support that. But the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported that some <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials believe <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s appointment indicated <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> may no longer be capable or willing to continue to run military affairs <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> has designated a senior cleric, <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein-Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Montazeri </PERSON>, as his successor. But <PERSON> Montazari </PERSON> is opposed by many leading figures and is widely expected to be little more than figurehead for a small group of political heavyweights led by the charismatic <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> after <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> dies. <PERSON> Khomeinis </PERSON> appointment of <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, long a close aide, as military leader underlined that <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> has his confidence and is apparently being groomed to hold the reins of power in the critical era that will follow <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s death. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> is also close to <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s son and confidant, <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON>.
