<HEAD>OTA Study Says Soviets Could Knock Out Anti-Missile System</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf bgng ``Pentagon and SDI ... '' to update with
reaction from SDI Organization.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> could launch nuclear-tipped rockets that would threaten to knock out the proposed early-round version of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Star Wars anti-missile system, a scientific study said Tuesday. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> system also would be threatened by the possibility that the enormously complex software needed to run its computers might fail the first and only time it would be used, the congressional <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION> said. The conclusions are part of a 2-year-long <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> study that raises new questions about <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s program, known formally the Strategic Defense Initiative. The Strategic Defense Initiative Organization, in a statement, said the report `` reflects a decidedly more constructive and balanced assessment than previous reports by OTA.'' But the statement disputed <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION>'s comments about computer software, claiming the study failed `` to acknowledge the positive achievements and the real operating record of such systems'' as the Safeguard ballistic missile defense, which operated for a 10-month period early in the last decade. The <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> study was publicly released despite the fact that the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> had refused to declassify three chapters dealing with ways the Soviets could counter the American system. When <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> announced his program in 1983, he proposed that it should be aimed at making nuclear weapons obsolete. SDI officials have been overseeing research into a wide variety of futuristic technologies, including lasers and beam weapons. But in the past two years, SDI officials and supporters of the program have been pushing for a less comprehensive `` phase one'' SDI system which could be started in the mid-1990s. The second and third phases of such a system would be constructed later. Last year, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that a phase one SDI system costing $ 75 billion to $ 150 billion could be deployed using a combination of ground-based rockets and space-based rockets that would be parked in orbiting `` garages,'' ready to fire at attacking Soviet missiles. But the Soviets could attack such a system with anti-satellite -LRB- ASAT -RRB- rockets using nuclear-tipped weapons, the <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> study said. The Soviets now have an operational ASAT system. The Soviet ASATs `` would pose a significant threat to all three defense system phases, but particularly to the first two,'' <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Such weapons deployed in quantity, especially with multiple decoys -LRB- to confuse the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> system -RRB- would threaten to degrade severely the performance of a first - or second-phase'' SDI system, the study said The study was the second OTA report critical of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Star Wars plan. Other scientific reports have also questioned the feasibility of SDI goals. The <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> study also raised questions about the software that would be used to run the SDI computers. Other studies have raised questions about whether reliable software, which would be far more complex than anything previously put together, can be developed. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karas </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> study, said there is `` a significant probability'' that the software would fail the first time it was used in a real situation. The study noted that `` the nature of software and experience with large, complex software systems indicate that there may always be irresolvable questions about how dependable'' the SDI programs `` would be and about the confidence the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could place in dependability estimates.'' In addition, any attempt to realistically test the software could only be done by computer simulation and thus it would also be dependent on software, <PERSON> Karas </PERSON> said. The study said there are `` no adequate models for the development, production, test and maintainance of software for full-scale'' missile defense systems. <PERSON> Karas </PERSON> said he did n't understand why public release of the three chapters had been refused by the Pentagon. They were so general that the Soviets could not likely gain much military advantage from reading the material, he said. The study said it was difficult to come up with a `` precise degree'' of how well the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> system could survive a Soviet attack because that would depend `` on the tactics employed by each side and on the evitable uncertainties of battle.'' The Democratic-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has consistently cut <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s requests for SDI spending The program is funded at $ 3.9 billion in the current fiscal year. For the 1989 fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has voted $ 4.6 billion while the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> has approved $ 3.5 billion, with a compromise to be worked out by a <ORGANIZATION> Senate-House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had sought $ 4.8 billion.
