<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government-controlled media still attack an opposition rendered voiceless by the closure of four newspapers, a television station and three radio stations critical of Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. `` I do not think they will allow the news media to reopen,'' <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Robles </PERSON>, director of the shuttered daily newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>, said of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s government. `` They can not co-exist with a free press. `` How can the government talk of elections next year when there is no freedom of the press?'' <PERSON> Robles </PERSON> said in a recent interview. The government has indicated that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who was indicted on charges of drug trafficking in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, may run for president in the May 1989 election. The dailies <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Siglo </PERSON> and Extra, the weekly Quiubo, Channel 5 television, and radio stations <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exitosa </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> KW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continente </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mundial </ORGANIZATION> also have been closed. All are owned by critics of the Noriega-controlled government. The media controlled by the government or sympathetic to <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> relentlessly criticize the opposition forces who want to oust the general, who as head of the nation's 15,000-member <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> is considered the country's de facto leader. The government's radio and television station and the three daily newspapers who support <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> constantly ridicule opposition leaders, often describing them as lackeys of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. They also criticize the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its allies. Last week, the daily <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republica </ORGANIZATION> said in a headline that President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> has cancer because he once kissed an American flag. Only <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estrella </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's oldest newspaper, sometimes gives space to opposition comment. Opposition efforts to obtain court orders or get official word about reopening have been fruitless. <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Prensa </PERSON> was first closed on July 26. It was allowed to reopen Jan. 20, shortly before President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> tried to fire <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> as head of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, who owns Channel 5, was instead deposed by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> supporters in the <ORGANIZATION> Legislative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. On Feb. 25, soldiers who said they were acting on the `` order of a higher authority'' closed down <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Prensa </PERSON> again. Police have since guarded the building. `` We have no access to our equipment or files in the building,'' said <PERSON> Robles </PERSON>. `` We can not find out who ordered the closing down of the newspaper, what we are accused of or what is going to happen.'' The newspaper filed suit against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, holding him responsible for the closure. But the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rejected the petition late last month, saying it had no jurisdiction and could not fix blame for the closure because the soldiers who shut down <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Prensa </PERSON> had no written orders. On Monday, nine officials from the attorney general's office and three police officers went to the <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prensa </LOCATION> building for what they described as an `` investigation.'' They refused to provide any details about their inquiry. <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Dario </PERSON> <PERSON> Carles </PERSON>, chairman of the board of <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>, said the paper will put its case before the <ORGANIZATION> InterAmerican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and appeal for support from the embassies of several Latin American countries.
