<HEAD>Bennett Says Chicago's `Worst' Schools Best Place To Try Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s public schools, labeled the worst in the nation by Education Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, could be the best place to try changes that would help students learn, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` There are radical proposals in the air,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. `` This may be a revolutionary time.'' Speaking to reporters after the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Foreign Relations, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> suggested the 430,000-pupil system consider a voucher plan in which parents could choose schools and the government would pick up the tab. `` If you tried it, tried it honestly and fairly, I would predict it would improve things dramatically,'' he said. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> also said the school system's bureaucracy was `` the blob.'' He called for redistributing power to give parents and local school principals more say over curriculum, personnel and other policies. Last November, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> called <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s public schools, plagued by low test scores and high dropout rates, the worst in the nation and an `` education meltdown.'' He later accused teachers' unions of blocking reform. He said Tuesday that his view of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s system has n't changed much. `` If it's not the worst, it's too ... close to the worst,'' he said. Nearly 45 percent of the students who began school with the class of 1985 dropped out before graduating. State figures also show that half of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s public high schools ranked in the bottom 1 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> schools for student scores on the American College Test. But <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said that whatever comes out of efforts to improve the schools `` may be able to point the way for other school systems in the country.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> stayed out of a fight in the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> over a state income tax increase, although he said `` I am not convinced that it takes money'' to change schools for the better. He said any new state money for education in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> must be tied to a reform package that would shift power in the system. `` You must give the people who run your schools the power, the autonomy, to run those schools,'' he said. `` Then you must hold them accountable for the results.'' Calling any reform that did n't redistribute power `` nonsense,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said unions interested only in `` getting more and more for everyone'' may be hurt in the short run. But positive changes in schools would help unions in the long run by raising the professional esteem of teachers. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> visited two <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> schools in March at the request of <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. He said afterward that `` intransigence of special interests'' such as unions remain the biggest obstacle to reform. <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Vaughn </PERSON>, president of the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> union, said then that cutbacks in government funds were the real culprits.
