<HEAD>East Wing Anniversary Show To Feature 20th Century Works</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 10th graf pvs, bgng: Gallery officials, with 1 graf
giving total of works in modern art collection, Brown quote.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The National Gallery of Art will celebrate the 10th anniversary of its modernistic East Building with a two-year exhibition of its small but rapidly growing collection of 20th century art, gallery officials said Tuesday. The show, which will open Dec. 4, will include about 250 works by modern artists ranging from <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON> to <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>. It will occupy more than half of the building's 55,000 square feet of gallery space on three of its five levels. `` The new exhibition will demonstrate our progress in expanding the gallery's collection of modern art,'' said director <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. About 60 percent of the paintings, sculptures and drawings in the show will come from the gallery's permanent collection. Half of those were acquired in the decade since the East Building opened on June 1, 1978. The remaining works will be on loan from private collections. Curator <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowart </PERSON> said that although the East Building was designed in part by architect I.M. <PERSON> Pei </PERSON> specifically to house the gallery's modern art collection, the only permanent exhibition site for those works has been on the less visible concourse or basement level of the building. <PERSON> Cowart </PERSON> said 20th century art was virtually non-existent at the National Gallery until the early 1960s, when the gallery received a gift of about 100 works of modern art from the <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> collection. Since then, he said, the gallery's collection has grown steadily with the goal of assembling a high-quality range of modern masters, although there is no pretense of matching the vast numbers of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Museum of Modern Art or Metropolitan Museum of Art. `` We acquire carefully, slowly and with great care,'' said <PERSON> Cowart </PERSON>, who estimated that about 90 percent of the gallery's acquisitions are gifts rather than purchases Two major gifts were made in 1986, when the gallery acquired more than 900 drawings and 100 paintings by American artist <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothko </PERSON> and `` The Stations of the Cross,'' a 15-painting series by <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON> <PERSON> Newman </PERSON>. The gallery's modern paintings, sculptures and decorative art objects have grown in the past decade from 272 to 613 works, compared with thousands in other collections. `` Our center of gravity is the old masters,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> conceded. The exhibition opening in December, involving extensive remodeling of the East Building's gallery spaces, will move 20th century art upstairs from the basement `` to give the collection a presence the public can count on,'' <PERSON> Cowart </PERSON> said. The tower and upper levels will feature pre-World War II artists such as <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON>, <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Matisse </PERSON>, <PERSON> Georges </PERSON> <PERSON> Braque </PERSON> and <PERSON> Amedeo </PERSON> <PERSON> Modigliani </PERSON>. The concourse galleries will highlight the works of postwar artists such as <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>, <PERSON> Newman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON>, <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lichtenstein </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jasper </PERSON> <PERSON> Johns </PERSON>. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said the exhibition may embark on a national tour once it closes at the East Building in December 1990.
