ral government's war on drug abuse in the three key areas of prevention, treatment and law enforcement,'' <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement released at the White House. `` Should <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> provide less than the president's request, programs to combat illegal drugs will suffer.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> graduating class last month that he wanted to see the national drug debate depoliticized, and he proposed creation of a joint executive-legislative task force to recommend solutions. But no such joint task force has yet been constituted, although <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., have study groups working on legislative proposals <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> said that under the legislation the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is poised to recommend: _ There would be no financing of 177 new drug enforcement agents and support positions, at a cost of $ 44 million Plans for expanded intelligence capabilities and equipment, including aircraft and computer equipment, would have to be canceled. _ The government would not be able to carry out a proposal to add 3,400 positions at a cost of $ 574 million to reinforce the federal prison system _ It would be impossible to create 566 additional <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney and support positions in the prosecution force, at a cost of $ 44 million, and the prosecution of major organized crime drug task force cases would be out of the question _ There would be no money for the anticipated addition 