<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The suicide rate among jail inmates is nine times greater than that of the general population and continues to be the leading cause of death in city and county lockups, according to a federally financed study released Tuesday. `` Although the average length of stay in jail is approximately 6 to 11 days, 51 percent of all jail suicide victims were dead within the first 24 hours of incarceration and 29 percent committed suicide within the first three hours,'' the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> on Institutions and Alternatives said. `` While alcohol-drug related and minor ` other' charges account for 37 percent of offenses for which jail inmates are confined, they represented 55 percent of all suicide victims,'' according to the study of jail suicides in 1985-86. <PERSON> Lindsay </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> directed the project, which was supported through a grant from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said the suicide rate in detention facilities was found to be 107 per 100,000 inmates. Census Bureau studies show, he said, that the rate is 12.5 per 100,000 in the general population. `` Further, suicide continues to be the leading cause of death in our nation's jails,'' <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said in a statement. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> recorded 32 percent of all the suicides in the study. Those states, according to <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> figures, also house one in three jail inmates. The numbers of suicides in jails was 453 in 1985 and 401 in 1986, the study said. The findings also showed that 72 percent of the suicide victims were white, 94 percent were male, the average age of the victim was 30, 60 percent of the victims were intoxicated at the time they were jailed and two of three victims were in isolation. `` While black inmates comprise 41 percent of the jail population, they acounted for only 16 percent of the jail suicides,'' the study said. `` While 31 percent of jail inmates are intoxicated by alcohol upon arrest, over 60 percent of jail suicide victims were intoxicated upon arrest.'' Only <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> recorded no jail suicides in the two-year period.
