<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Flint </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, developer of a worldwide agricultural research network which has increased the availability of food for billions of people, was named Tuesday to receive the $ 200,000 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prize </ORGANIZATION>. `` This was a total surprise to me,'' <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said of the award given to recognize outstanding achievement in improving the quantity, quality or availability of food on a significant world scale. <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, who will celebrate his 81st birthday on June 22, told a news conference that world governments must `` support and strengthen ... the connection between the research worker, the extension worker -LRB- in the field -RRB- and the farmer'' to increase world food production. `` We must meet the farmer where he is,'' he said, noting that `` the farmer is not very often the limiting factor'' in the success of agricultural programs in foreign lands. Instead, <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said, `` it's the extension agent who wants to make sure it's the right thing he's recommending or government officials who are n't ready to support -LRB- new agricultural -RRB- innovations.'' <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, who was chosen from a field of 125 nominees from 39 nations, will receive his cash award and an original sculpture by <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> during a ceremony at the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> on Oct. 4. The prize, first awarded in 1987, is funded by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit arm of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ