<HEAD>Iran-Contra Prosecutor Accused of Illegally Using Free Legal Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three conservatives filed a complaint Tuesday against independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, saying the Iran-Contra prosecutor may have violated federal criminal law when he accepted free legal services from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> law professor <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Tribe </PERSON>. Tribe, at <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s behest, wrote a brief in support of another independent counsel, <PERSON> Alexia </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, who is seeking to have the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> reverse a federal appeals court decision which declared that independent counsels are unconstitutional. The criminal complaint filed with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s criminal division says <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> may have violated the Anti-Deficiency Act, which makes it unlawful for a government employee to accept voluntary services from private individuals <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said his office had researched the question and concluded there was no violation, and that his office was checking with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on the matter. The complaint was filed by three men, including <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Messing </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. Messing is a conservative activist who worked with fired <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> in attempts to aid the Contras. The complaint asks the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to look into the free services of Tribe and calls for appointment of an independent counsel to conduct a criminal investigation. The maximum penalty for violating the Anti-Deficiency Act is two years imprisonment and a $ 5,000 fine. The others filing the complaint were <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Boehm </PERSON>, treasurer of the Conservative Campaign Fund, and <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Flaherty </PERSON>, chairman of Citizens for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. `` We have carefully researched this issue and are satsified that there is no violation whatever of the Anti-Deficiency Act,'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said in a statement. `` We have communicated this conclusion to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which has expressed no disagreement and has sought the views of its office of legal counsel,'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> added. The Citizens for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> group issued a statement quoting <PERSON> Boehm </PERSON> as saying `` <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> has sought to privatize our judicial process.'' <PERSON> Flaherty </PERSON> said that `` one must question the financial arrangements'' in which <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> is allowing senior staff lawyers to retain their relationships with private law firms. <PERSON> Flaherty </PERSON> said this has created `` the potential for huge conflicts of interest.'' A spokesman for <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wieghart </PERSON>, said a special panel screens potential conflicts of interest and that `` we're aware of none.'' <PERSON> Wieghart </PERSON> said <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> tried to get the most qualified lawyers possible for his investigation and acknowledged that some have come to work on a part-time basis.
