<HEAD>Governent Ordered to Grant Visas to Four Barred Due to Communist
Affiliations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge Tuesday ordered the government to grant visas to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s interior minister and three others barred from entering the country because of their membership in communist or communist-affiliated groups. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, reversing an earlier finding that had been set aside by a federal appeals court, ruled that Nicaraguan Interior Minister <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Borge </PERSON>, two Cuban officials and a former Italian senator should be admitted to accept speaking engagements at the invitation of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens. <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> held that the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had violated the 1952 Immigration and Nationality Act by denying the four visas simply because the applicants were members of communist or communist-affiliated organizations. The law authorizes the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to exclude aliens if a consular official determines they would engage in activities during a visit that `` would be prejudicial to the public interest'' or endanger the safety of citizens. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had invoked the 1952 law saying that visits by <PERSON> Borge </PERSON>, former Italian senator <PERSON> Nino </PERSON> <PERSON> Pasti </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> officials <PERSON> Leonor </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Lezcano </PERSON> and <PERSON> Olga </PERSON> <PERSON> Finlay </PERSON> would be prejudicial to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interests. <PERSON> Borge </PERSON> had been invited in 1983 to speak by members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, university professors and religious leaders, but the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said his presence in the country would be `` highly prejudicial to the foreign policy interests of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' To keep <PERSON> Pasti </PERSON> out, the government cited his membership in the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, a group it considered controlled by the Soviet government, and said his speech to a nuclear disarmament rally on <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> would merely advance Soviet interests. The two <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> women had been delegates to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on the Statute of Women and were invited by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to attend a conference on the subject. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> argued that to bar someone, the law requires the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to determine that an alien's proposed activities during the visit _ as opposed to political affiliations _ would endanger <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interests <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> originally sided with the government's application of the law, but a divided panel of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here reversed his 1984 ruling. The appellate court finding was upheld last fall on a 3-3 vote by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, which did not issue an opinion. The appellate panel ordered <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> to determine if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had acquiesced to a longstanding <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> practice of refusing visas to individuals simply because their mere presence in the country would hurt national interests. `` In the opinion of this court, the government has failed in this task,'' <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said in Tuesday's ruling. `` The court finds that the evidence of administrative acquiesence is only imperceptibly more weighty than it was when these cases were before the court in 1984.'' <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenberg </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> lawyer in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> who worked on the case, said <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>'s ruling means `` you ca n't penalize individuals for their associational activities, for their expression and for their ideology.'' `` We believe the statute looked to conduct,'' he said.
