<HEAD>Bulgarian Joins 2 Soviets in First Manned Flight of 1988</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS time conversion in 2d graf pvs, Alexander Alexandrov
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Soviet cosmonauts and a Bulgarian rocketed into space Tuesday on the first manned flight of 1988, riding a column of orange flame on live television, courtesy of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and `` glasnost.'' <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON>, 36, from the Bulgarian town of <LOCATION> Omurtag </LOCATION>, had waited more than nine years for the flight. The Soyuz TM-5 space capsule lifted off at 6:03 p.m. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> time -LRB- 10:03 a.m. EDT -RRB- from the Baikonur Cosmodrome in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. The broadcast on state television showed flames spewing from a Vostok rocket booster to lift the capsule into a nearly cloudless blue sky. `` I feel excellent,'' <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON> said from inside the capsule seconds after the launch. The shot, in black and white, showed him in cramped quarters. About two minutes into the flight, the first stage of the booster dropped away and plummeted toward the earth. Before <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> became the Soviet leader, with his `` glasnost'' policy of openness in selected areas, launches customarily were broadcast only when successful and only on tape, after the fact. Tuesday's live coverage lasted more than an hour, and other media also featured the story. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> carrried 10 reports on the launch and the Soviet manned space program. The Soviet program thrives, while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manned flights stalled after January 1986 explosion of the space shuttle Challenger, which killed seven astronauts. Several other Soviet manned missions are planned for this year, including crew members from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. During the broadcast Tuesday, <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON>'s family was shown in <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> watching the launch on a television screen set up on a street. `` I wish him a happy journey and a safe return, like any mother,'' his mother told a television reporter minutes after the launch. The broadcast showed cheering, waving crowds in the streets. <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>'s defense minister was among the dignitaries watching at Baikonur in the republic of <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON> and cosmonauts <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Savinykh </PERSON>, 48, and <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Y. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solovyov </PERSON>, 40, are scheduled to dock Thursday with the space station Mir, whose name means Peace in Russian. Already aboard are cosmonauts <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Titov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Musa </PERSON> <PERSON> Manarov </PERSON>, the last men to enter space. They reached the station Dec. 23. In a 10-day mission, the five men are to conduct about 40 experiments, some using Bulgarian equipment. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, the official news agency, said they involve space physics, remote sensing of <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, space biology and medicine. Among items the new cosmonauts are taking to the Mir is an orchid grown on Earth from seeds planted on the space station, the agency said. <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Svirin </PERSON>, a shift director at the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kaliningrad </LOCATION>, northeast of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, told reporters the Mir's amenities include a a videocassette recorder with which the cosmonauts can watch movies The last Bulgarian-Soviet flight, in April 1979, was marred by a failed attempt to dock with the Salyut space station. The Bulgarian cosmonaut on that flight, <PERSON> Georgy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON>, told Soviet television this time he had one wish for <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON>: that he only hear the word `` normal'' during his mission. <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON> got his wish. <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> said repeatedly that all systems on the Soyuz TM-5 were operating normally. <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON> was the backup Bulgarian for the 1979 mission. He had trained for this flight since last year.
