<HEAD>Najib Says One-Fourth Of Soviets Withdrawn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> said Tuesday more than 34,000 Soviet soldiers _ about 30 percent of the total _ have been withdrawn but the pace may be slowed if <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> continues arming Afghan insurgents. `` If the Pakistani side does not ... end interference in the internal affairs of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> from its territory, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> reserves its right to react to this in a manner warranted,'' <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, who uses only one name, said in a speech to a special <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> session on disarmament. He did not elaborate in the speech, but told a news conference later: `` We want to visualize an optimistic situation ... but should such violations acquire a permanent character ... in such a case we would certainly renew our consideration on the schedule of withdrawal and take proper reactions, together with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> added, however, that his government intends to meet the troop withdrawal schedule set by the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement with <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which requires all Soviet soldiers to be out within nine months of May 15. In his first speech to the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, delivered in the <LOCATION> Dari </LOCATION> language, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> accused Pakistani authorities and Afghan guerrillas of hindering the voluntary return of Afghan refugees to their homeland. `` Such actions are sheer violations of the letter and spirit of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords and an affront to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. `` They in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> will be gravely mistaken should they think that only one part of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords, the return of the Soviet troops, will be implemented and the other parties will not live up to their commitments,'' <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> said. About 5.5 million people, roughly one-third of the population, have fled <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in 10 years of civil war _ more than 3 million to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and 2 million to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The U.N.-mediated agreement signed April 14 in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> requires the Soviets to withdraw the more than 100,000 <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> soldiers who have been helping fight Moslem rebels in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Soviet officials also have threatened to slow the withdrawal. In a statement May 28 announcing that 10,000 soldiers had left <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said the pullout could slow if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> kept delivering `` lavish supplies'' to the rebels. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> spoke to the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> disarmament session for 30 minutes, devoting most of his remarks to the situation in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. He again called for national reconciliation and establishment of a coalition government, including opposition forces. He said the death toll in the war was 243,900 soldiers and civilians, including 35,700 women and 20,700 children. He said 77,700 people have been wounded. Moslem guerrillas began fighting in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> after a Communist coup in April 1978 and Soviet military forces entered the country in December 1979. The insurgents were not involved in the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> negotiations. Leaders of the seven-party guerrilla coalition have said they would ignore the agreement and continue fighting.
