<HEAD>Toxic Wastes From Italy Dumped in Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 2,400 tons of toxic waste from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> have been dumped in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, maritime authorities revealed Tuesday. The poisonous chemicals were shipped to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in containers and barrels to be dumped in the Kesrouan coastal strip, about 20 miles north of the capital city of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, the authorities said. Some of the waste material was left in barrels in the <LOCATION> Kesrouan </LOCATION> area, authorities said. Some reports say part of the shipment was buried in that region. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Farhat </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters investigations were under way to determine how the chemicals entered <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Lebanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> TV station, said Monday a <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> importer, identified only as <PERSON> Haddad </PERSON>, concluded an agreement with an Italian chemical firm for bringing the waste into <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s telecommunications authority intercepted a message from the importer to his Italian agent demanding $ 500,000 for his services. Interior Minister <PERSON> Abdullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Rassi </PERSON> said the waste was being examined to see if it was radioactive. The reports came as the Syrian freighter <LOCATION> Zanooria </LOCATION> was docked in <LOCATION> Genoa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, waiting to unload more than 2,000 tons of unidentified industrial waste that first sailed from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> last year. Various countries refused to accept the wastes.
