<FIRST>u w AM-AntitrustGuidelines     06-07 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Antitrust Guidelines,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Issues New Guidelines for International Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday proposed new antitrust guidelines for international operations that generally give greater flexibility to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and foreign firms to engage in cooperative ventures. The draft would replace guidelines issued more than a decade ago, which have become `` badly outdated'' due to changes in federal law, developments in case law and changes in economic thinking, said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Rule </PERSON>, assistant attorney general for the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s antitrust division. The 1977 guidelines were `` very restrictive and hostile'' to intellectual property licensing agreements, said Rule. Under the new guidelines, such agreements wo n't be challenged unless it is found they will drastically raise prices to consumers or unduly restrict output. The 1977 guidelines provided an `` ill-defined analysis'' for what types of joint ventures were permitted, said Rule, who contended that the proposal provides a `` structured approach.'' A summary of the draft guidelines says that joint research and development, technology licensing restrictions and vertical non-price distribution arrangements `` often are not anti-competitive, and often substantially benefit <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. consumers.'' `` The most important thing the new guidelines do is provide certainty and clarity in the law, which reduces the cost of international transactions and increases the competitve ability of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firms and ultimately enhances the welfare of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumers,'' Rule said. The proposed guidelines contain 17 hypothetical cases of ways in which the new policies would apply. The new guidelines say the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s top enforcement priority in the antitrust area internationally remains the prosecution of `` naked'' cartel arrangements among competitors engaging in price-fixing and bid-rigging agreements.
