<HEAD>Spectators Scuffle With Officer, Get Arrested Outside Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two spectators at a court hearing on conditions at a federal prison in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> were held Tuesday on charges they assaulted a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marshal. The two men, believed to be supporters of a prisoner who testified at the hearing, were arrested after they scuffled with a deputy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marshal outside the courtroom of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Barrington </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, according to federal law enforcement authorities. The incident occurred while <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> was conducting a hearing on a lawsuit challenging conditions at a high-security isolation unit for a half-dozen women prisoners at the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> had heard testimony about prison conditions from prisoner <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON>, identified by law enforcement officials as a left-wing terrorist who is serving a 58-year prison term for possessing 600 pounds of weapons and explosives Ms. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> is among seven people recently indicted for placing a bomb that exploded in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Capitol in 1983. One of the two men in police custody following the hallway scuffle had refused to stand up when the judge returned from an afternoon recess, said authorities. When asked by <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> why he had not stood up, the man said he did not respect the authority of the court. Authorities said Deputy U.S. Marshal <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickett </PERSON> was jumped from behind while escorting the man down a hallway outside <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>'s courtroom <PERSON> Pickett </PERSON> was then punched by the man he was escorting before he and other courthouse guards subdued his attackers, authorities said. The two men, identified only as <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heild </PERSON> and <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wardlaw </PERSON>, were being held in the city police lockup Tuesday night on charges they assaulted a marshal, said authorities, who spoke on condition of anonymity. Ms. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> and two other inmates, <PERSON> Sylvia </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> and <PERSON> Silvia </PERSON> <PERSON> Baraldini </PERSON>, charge in the lawsuit brought by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> that they are being held in the <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> isolation unit because of their political beliefs. <PERSON> Baraldini </PERSON> was convicted of racketeering and conspiracy in aiding a bungled $ 1.6 million robbery of a Brink's armored car in <LOCATION> Nyack </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, that left a guard and two police officers dead in 1981. At the unit in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, guards escort the prisoners to and from the locked cellblock. Prisoners' hands and feet are shackled every time they leave the unit, Ms. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON>, who was in the general populations of two other federal prisons, said authorities told her she was placed in the unit in October, 1986 because she was considered a terrorist. `` They said I had a one-way ticket,'' she told <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>. `` The isolation and the control and the dependency has taken away any semblance of any kind of self-determination about my life,'' Ms. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> said. `` Nobody should have that happen to them, no matter what they've been convicted of. That's punishment on punishment.'' `` I really think that in prison you ca n't control all aspects of your life,'' Ms. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> said. `` But when you ca n't control anything at any level, that's out of your hands, the frustration is really unbearable.'' Ms. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> said the isolation and strict control by guards has inflicted severe emotional and psychological stress. `` Trying to suppress the anger asks an enormous amount of energy, an enormous amount of self-control and it's making me sick,'' she said. Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Logan </PERSON>, a psychiatrist hired by the government to inspect the prison, testified that he found no evidence that conditions had caused any unusual emotional or psychological damage. But <PERSON> Logan </PERSON> said his findings were based only on observations and conversations with prison doctors because the prisoners refused to talk to him. Federal authorities contend that the extra security is required to protect the facility from terrorist attack. They said they plan to move the unit to a prison in <LOCATION> Mariana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, in July. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinlan </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prisons </ORGANIZATION>, in a 1987 letter to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, denied that inmates are sent to the unit because of political beliefs. But affiliation with groups that use violence in `` attempts to disrupt or overthrow the government of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, or whose published ideology includes advocating law violations in order to ` free' prisoners is a factor,'' he said. Last weekend, <PERSON> Lynette </PERSON> <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> `` Squeaky'' <PERSON> Fromme </PERSON>, convicted of trying to shoot President Ford on Sept 5, 1975 in <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, was transferred to the unit last weekend, authorities said.
