 A man went on a rampage Tuesday in a road grader and badly damaged at least three planes at the airport here before he was shot by police and sheriff's deputies, authorities said. The man, identified as <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> LaComb </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Anaheim </LOCATION>, was shot several times below the waist, said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bernardino </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. No other injuries were reported. <PERSON> LaComb </PERSON>, 37, was airlifted to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> where he was listed in stable condition, <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said. Authorities said he was charged with assault with a deadly weapon. Police and sheriff's deputies on the ground and a sheriff's deputy in a helicopter opened fire on the man after he ran into the side of Flight Craft, a business that gives flight lessons and refuels planes at the airport <LOCATION> Chino </LOCATION> is located about 40 miles east of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. <PERSON> LaComb </PERSON> is a construction worker in the area and had access to the grader, but he took it out of the authorized area on his day off, another sheriff's spokesman said. The chase began in the <LOCATION> Chino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> area, about six miles west of the airport, after the sheriff's station received a complaint at 9:41 a.m. that someone was operating a road grader in an erratic manner, <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said. Chino police detectives began chasing the grader during the 29-minute drive to the airport, during which several people were nearly hit, he said. During the five-minute rampage at the airport, <PERSON> LaComb </PER