<HEAD>Soviet Journal Criticizes Lenin For Harsh Policies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet literary journal has taken a new look at <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>, saying the country's founder tried to enforce tough economic policies by ordering executions and other tough measures that backfired. In a 30-page article in the May edition of Novy Mir -LRB- New World -RRB-, <PERSON> Vassily </PERSON> <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON>, takes a more realistic look at <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>'s policies than the Lenin-can-do-no-wrong approach that has dominated official Soviet news media for years. <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON> said that in the first few years after the Bolshevik Revolution in 1917, <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> favored extremely harsh measures for putting the economy on track. `` The extremes of force, as we see, spread boundlessly: first it is undertaken for repression of opponents of the revolution, then it is turned against potential enemies -LRB- the Red Terror -RRB- and finally, it becomes a means for solving purely economic tasks,'' <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON> wrote. Selyunin seemed to imply <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> laid the seeds for the abuses of power for which his successor, <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, has been condemned. Under Kremlin leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, historians are being encouraged to take a more honest look at the country's past. The result has been numerous press articles, books and films blasting <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, who was responsible for the deaths of millions. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> attacked <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s economic policies, under which the central government tightly controlled production and allowed little individual initiative. The criticism extended to the `` era of stagnation'' under <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, who ruled the country from the early 1960s to 1982. But criticism of <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> has been off-limits. The Novy Mir article says <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> was mistaken when he abolished all private property and created a system of forced labor camps. <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> started to go astray in November 1917, when he declared that `` speculators'' were `` enemies of the people'' who should be shot when found, according to <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON>. Speculation meant anything outside government trade. <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> also advocated another harsh measure, limiting peasant families to only the bread they needed to make it to the next harvest, <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON> wrote. The penalty for violation was a minimum 10-year jail term. The author says <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> might be excused for some of the measures because the country was suffering severe hunger and destruction. But, <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON> wrote, the harsh measures actually made the problems worse. In January 1918, <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> supported a decree that increased prison space so `` class enemies'' could be incarcerated. But <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> began to realize he was wrong, and <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON> quotes him as saying the use of force was backfiring in that it was increasing civil unrest, according to the article. In March 1921, <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> made a midcourse correction and had a severe tax removed from peasants. Two months later he launched his New Economic Policy, which allowed greater freedom in agriculture, industry and trade. Selyunin credits this program with helping rid the country of bureaucracy, which <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has said is stifling some of his reforms.
