l </LOCATION> does not allow international inspection of its nuclear plants, a requirement of the Non-Proliferation Treaty. `` Many have urged us to sign the Non-Proliferation Treaty,'' said <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>. But we have seen that this treaty has, in no way, prevented wars between its signatories. ... We have repeatedly invited the Arab states to negotiate the establishment of a nuclear-weapon-free zone, but they have rejected the idea. ... They have refused to negotiate with us.'' He condemned the use of chemical weapons and poison gas in the Iran-Iraq war, singling out <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> _ `` By its own admission, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has used this vicious means of indiscriminate killing in its war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. It is a gross and blatant violation of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> Protocol, to which <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> is a signatory.'' Delegates from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> walked out before <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> began speaking. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> also called for the reduction of conventional forces in the region. He decried the introduction of medium-range missiles in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> was one of about 25 presidents and prime ministers due to address the special session on disarmament, which opened last week and is expected to end June 25.
