<HEAD>Slain DEA Agent Pleaded With Captors to End Beatings, Tapes Reveal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal drug agent pleaded with his Mexican abductors to stop beating him during interrogation before he was murdered, according to transcripts of tape recordings filed in federal court. Transcripts of two tapes obtained by Mexican authorites from the home of reputed drug kingpin Ernesto Fonseca-Carrillo were filed Monday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> as part of the prosecution of three of the nine men indicted in the murder of <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON>. <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> agent, was kidnaped Feb. 7, 1985 as he left the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Consulate in <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION>. Several weeks later his body and that of his pilot, <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavala-Avelar </PERSON>, who was kidnapped separately, were found on a remote ranch 70 miles away. <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> had been severely beaten. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have said <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> was kidnapped shortly after he and other agents uncovered a drug trafficking operation run by <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Caro-Quintero </PERSON>, who along with <PERSON> Fonseca-Carrillo </PERSON> was one of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s biggest drug kingpins. <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> moans and complains of pains and injuries on the tapes. Federal prosecutors say they believe the recorder was turned off during beatings. The agent says at one point that he has `` sharp pains'' all over his body and asks his captors: `` Could n't I ask you to have my ribs bandaged, please?'' Affidavits about autopsy reports, which also were filed, state that <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON>'s jaw was broken in several places and his head was shattered `` like an eggshell.'' According to documents filed in court, federal prosecutors believe that <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Espino-Verdin </PERSON>, a former Mexican police sergeant, interrogated <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> for two days at a large estate owned by Fonseca-Carrillo outside <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION>. Prosecutors said the voices of Espino-Verdin and <PERSON> Caro-Quintero </PERSON> have been identified on the tape. The transcript reveals that <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> told his captors the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> knew the whereabouts of Fonseca-Carrillo and Caro-Quintero but that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agents in <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION> were not allowed to carry weapons and so did n't conduct surveillance of the two men. `` To conduct surveillance over there at the house, I have never, sir ... I am afraid,'' <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> said. `` I did not want trouble. I just wanted to get out of here,'' he said, referring to his transfer back to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that was pending at the time. <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> may have been attempting to mislead his abductors by asserting that agents do n't carry guns, said <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lockridge </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Local commanders can authorize agents to carry weapons, he said. `` He was just throwing out something that was wrong,'' <PERSON> Lockridge </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> mentions confidential information at times, indicating that the tapes are authentic, according to affidavits of <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> agents who worked with him. That information includes a reference to complaints about the <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION> office from DEA headquarters. `` I'm telling you that we are being reprimanded from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> because, according to them, we are not working here,'' <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> says. `` As I say, well, who is going to do the work if they have one unarmed?'' <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> gave only skimpy information about <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> informants, causing the interrogator to snap: `` Who is it that put the finger on <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON>? Do n't tell me about your problems; speak of the information you can give us, you can provide us to finish with this bunch of jerks ...'' `` Yes, sir. What more can I tell you, sir?'' <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> says in a voice described in the transcript as `` very weak.'' Defense motions have challenged the validity of the tapes, saying they contain an unexplained burst of music and clicking sounds that suggest tampering or fabrication. <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez-Alvarez </PERSON>, 28, <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Felix-Gutierrez </PERSON>, 38, and <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Verdugo-Urquidez </PERSON>, 36, are scheduled to go on trial in <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Court </LOCATION> here later this month. All have denied involvement in the <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> case. Caro-Quintero and Fonseca-Carrillo are in custody in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and extradition proceedings are stalled. The other indicted men are not in custody.
