<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The White House AIDS commission gave its tentative endorsement Tuesday night to the bulk of the 579 recommendations the panel's chairman wants to put in a report to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> later this month. In releasing his recommendations last week, retired <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Adm. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> portrayed most of them as reflecting what he read as the consensus of the 13-member committee. That turned out to be true during an 11-hour meeting as the commissioners worked through the report page-by-page, making only minor changes in wording and organization. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>' had predicted correctly that his final chapter calling for legislation to vest sweeping new powers in the surgeon general _ currently Dr. <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> _ would prove controversial. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> should immediately proclaim AIDS a national emergency as soon as legislation is passed setting up a new framework within the government health bureaucracy to put the surgeon general in charge of dealing with it. Although the commission did not reject <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>' suggestions outright, there was a sharp exchange of differences between the chairman and commissioner <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> and it was clear <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> does not have the broad backing of the panel on his proposed shift of power to the surgeon general. The issue of what, if anything, to recommend in the way of administrative changes to deal with AIDS as well as future epidemics was left up in the air with the commissioners agreeing to submit their thoughts in writing for the panel's staff to synthesize and present for further consideration at the final working session next Thursday and Friday. The final report is due June 24 at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and it became clear after Tuesday's session that it will essentially track <PERSON> Watkin </PERSON>'s recommendations _ including his call for strong federal legislation to protect people with the AIDS virus from discrimination. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> told fellow commissioners he has received letters from `` both sides of the aisle'' that leads him to believe `` there is a feeling of momentum in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>'' for passage of such legislation despite administration opposition. `` It is something that can be done in this session of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. `` I do n't know that it will be.'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> had expressed some concern about the anti-discrimination recommendation in early discussions, saying it `` would not be fruitful and would not be fair'' to make a specific recommendation about AIDS discrimination. `` If we're going to make it, we should expand it to cover not just AIDS, but all diseases,'' said <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, the director of Project HOPE, a private international health delivery organization. However, other commissioners noted that the recommendation is for a law that spells out that people with the AIDS virus are to be treated just like people with any other handicapping disease _ no worse, no better. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said the anti-discrimination recommendation should be the No. 1 priority in the final report's introductory chapter. Among the other <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> recommendations the panel agreed to emphasize at the forefront of the final report: _ That all of those infected with the AIDS virus _ an estimated 1.5 million Americans compared with fewer than 70,000 actually diagnosed with the full-blown illness _ should be considered part of the epidemic _ That intravenous drug abuse is a national emergency that must be successfully dealt with if the AIDS epidemic is to be curtailed _ That the fight against the disease will require resources of private as well as government resources _ That compassion for those with AIDS should be empasized at all levels Tuesday's marathon session was designed to reach as much consensus as possible. Any lingering differences over final wording will be resolved by votes, if necessary, at next week's sessions. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> assured panel members there would be ample time for debate, promising to run the planned Thursday-Friday session into the weekend if necessary. AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it incapable of resisting other diseases and infections. The virus most often is spread through close contact with blood, blood products or semen from infected persons. Its chief victims have been homosexual men and intravenous drug users. As of June 6, AIDS had been diagnosed in 64,506 Americans, of whom more than half, or 36,255 have died since June 1981, according to the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. No one is known to have recovered from AIDS.
