<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Sandinista government and U.S.-backed rebels held daylong talks Tuesday on a government proposal for democratic reform in exchange for rebel disarmament. The fourth round of peace talks resumed Tuesday in a climate of mutual distrust, but both sides said they might be nearing agreement after more than six years of war. Information Minister <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Espinoza </PERSON> reported after the talks adjourned at 7 p.m. -LRB- 5 p.m. EDT -RRB- Tuesday until 9 a.m. Wednesday, `` We have made substantial advances.'' A representative of the leftist government, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said earlier that the government proposal bows to almost all the rebel demands for democratic reforms. The rebels, known as Contras, described the proposal as vague but said it raised hopes for an agreement. Contra negotiator <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> said: `` The Nicaraguan Resistance is here with a political decision to sign a definite agreement for permanent and lasting peace in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> if the government shows its political commitment to make the democratic reforms in this country to achieve that lasting peace.'' The Resistance is the Contras' umbrella organization. <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> <PERSON> Mamatoros </PERSON>, spokesman for the rebels, told reporters after the meeting ended `` there were advances in the discussion on themes of a substantial character,'' but said political reform remained `` the biggest problem in the discussions.'' He charged that the government was `` using the dialogue to gain time. They have to demonstrate the opposite to us.'' The talks are taking place amid a temporary truce enacted March 21. The rebels have extended the truce until Thursday, and the government has declared a unilateral cease-fire until the end of June. Each side accuses the other of violations. The government proposal promises press freedom, the right to strike, electoral reforms, an end to Sandinista control of the army and freedom for political prisoners. The proposal offers the Contras a role in talks begun late last year with opposition political parties. The so-called national dialogue has made little headway. On April 26, the opposition parties suspended the talks pending settlement of a workers' strike. The scars and bitterness of the civil war were dramatized Tuesday in dramatic full-page ads by the <ORGANIZATION> Mothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heroes </ORGANIZATION> and Martyrs in the two pro-government newspapers. The committee is comprised of mothers whose children have died in the war. The ad in the Barricada newspaper showed pictures of wounded children along with rebel commander Col. <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON>. `` We do n't want amnesty for criminals,'' it said. The ad in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nuevo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diario </LOCATION> showed women carrying a coffin, a child leaning on a cross and a bullet-riddled body. `` We wo n't forget,'' it said. `` Our pain calls for justice.'' The Sandinistas have called for disarmament of the rebels to be completed by September while the Contras have proposed January. The Contras say they will not lay down arms until the nation of 3 million people is a democracy. The Sandinistas say it already is. Vice President <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> said Monday night the Contras should accept the Sandinista proposals because `` at best, within a month they will not have the capacity to negotiate more.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid to the rebels ended on Feb. 26. Three weeks later, the rebels signed a temporary cease-fire and began talks on a permanent peace with the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>. The Contras are also plagued by deep divisions within their ranks. The Sandinistas, who get military and economic aid from the Soviet bloc, also have compelling reasons for ending a war that has claimed 26,000 lives. The Nicaraguan economy is a shambles and the government faces widespread public dissatisfaction over chronic shortages and its failure to deliver on promises made when it took power in July 1979. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> expressed hope that the talks would be productive and that the Sandinistas would negotiate in good faith. `` The key issue is the Sandinistas' willingness to democratize,'' Ms. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said. `` We're hopeful, but we note that in recent weeks the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> have increased repression of the internal opposition.''
