<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 City authorities tried to head off a planned pro-democracy march by university students on Wednesday by warning that demonstrations without approval are illegal. They urged students to `` keep a sober mind.'' In front-page editorials, major official dailies accused some student leaders of being agitators trying to negate <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s reforms and appealed to students to avoid the `` methods of anarchy.'' The planned Wednesday afternoon march to <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, the symbolic political center of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, would be the first major political protest by students since the winter of 1986-1987. Nationwide student unrest then led to a conservative backlash against Western liberal ideas. <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON> was removed as <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief for failing to stem the pro-democracy movement. The party purged several outspoken political thinkers. More than 1,000 students rallied from Tuesday night into early Wednesday at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s leading university, to voice demands for greater democracy, more press freedom, better living conditions for intellectuals and better campus security. The turmoil was prompted by the June 2 slaying of a university student in an off-campus brawl. Six non-students were arrested in the death. The killing brought to the surface student unhappiness over poor living conditions on campus and bleak economic prospects after graduation for the nation's low-paid intellectuals. Hundreds have gathered on the campus in the evenings for impromptu debates on what broader lessons are to be learned from the incident. Dozens of posters have gone up demanding democracy, a free press, an end to government corruption and petty bureaucracy and greater respect and higher salaries for intellectuals. I