<FIRST>s a BC-APN--Classof'38 Adv19-4Takes   06-07 1137</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Class of '38, Adv 19-4 Takes,1164</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv19</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&amp;w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ They came to college during the Great Depression. They graduated, worked hard and shaped fulfilling lives. When the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION>'s class of'38 held its 50th reunion recently, reporter <PERSON> Sid </PERSON> <PERSON> Moody </PERSON> _ who had chronicled their 25th in 1963 _ returned to round out their passage through five eventful decades. Their story, as he presents it, is a memorable yearbook of half a century of history as ordinary Americans lived it.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SID MOODY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This spring, in the autumn of their time, they returned to where they once had been young. `` Red clay people from a red clay state,'' said one in the class of 1938 at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION>. Once, maybe. Not now. Thunderheads darkened the evening sky that June 7, 1938 when they were given a diploma in one hand, a Bible in the other. Unforeseen winds were to strew them across the globe in a half-century of bearing witness. Depression. Three wars _ a victory, a standoff and a defeat _ burying their loss from each. The Bomb. <PERSON> Ike </PERSON>. JFK. Watergate. Heart transplants. The Bomb. 747s. TV. The'60s. The Bomb. LSD. PCs. PCBs. The Bomb. Once poor, they raised families in a flood tide of prosperity. And the Japanese cars some drove back to their 50th reunion gave a hint, perhaps, of its ebb. What their nation has seen and become, they have seen and become. They are a yearbook of their times.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Hold up your head and be yourself.'' _ From `` Be Yourself,'' by <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Flanner </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>: Permanent class president ... <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> med school ... combat surgeon in <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION>. Illness ended surgical career. Studied three years in mid-life while raising four children to become anesthesiologist. Wo n't retire. Instead, travels the country and beyond usually with wife, <PERSON> Alice </PERSON>, and Lab, <PERSON> Beau </PERSON>, in camper surveying hospitals for accreditation. `` Something I've learned which <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> knew all along: If you do n't have a goal even at our age, maybe especially at our age, life can be difficult. During the war in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> `` Pat'' was on the faculty at <ORGANIZATION> UNC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>. In his quiet way he proposed that his fellow doctors should do something to help the children maimed by that conflict. The majority demurred. Too political. `` If you're so concerned about those kids,'' said one. `` why do n't you go over there yourself, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON>?'' A lifetime in medicine had taught <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, son of a doctor, grandson of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senator, this: `` A good doctor is a person who with a clear mind and proper training cares for his patients to the best of his ability in a humane way.'' So he went to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to heal children. Twice.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Human rights _ freedom rights _ education's tallest heights.'' _ From `` Dr. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>,'' by <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Dr. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>: <ORGANIZATION> President </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> 1931-49. Died 1971. Dr. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> is remembered by his former students of'38 as the best of men in the worst of times. He was a focus of rectitude and example when a quarter of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> work force was unemployed; when ` Hoover carts,' wagons with rubber tires, replaced too-expensive tin lizzies; when cotton was 7.9 cents a pound and the new minimum wage a quarter; when a third of his 3,207 students worked their way through raking leaves, stoking furnaces to meet an average of $ 406.50 in annual fees. Hang on, he would urge his students at his Sunday open house, I'll go to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to get the money. The UNC of the'30s strikes a bittersweet, simpler nostalgia today. In 1938 there was a waiting line for the 100 copies of `` Gone With the Wind'' on loan at the library. For a dime you could see <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Gable </PERSON>, <PERSON> Myrna </PERSON> <PERSON> Loy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> at the movies in `` Test Pilot.'' `` Our Town,'' <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>'s small-town epic, won the Pulitzer for drama. Harsh reality was buried under corsages, crepe ribbons and ball gowns as the class of'38 danced in the transformed field house, The Tin Can, to <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Kayser </PERSON> or the <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON> brothers. Seventy-nine of 89 coeds said they'd go no farther than a goodnight kiss. But there were harbingers, unsuspected, among the dogwood. In <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> TV signals had been beamed 220 miles. In <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fritz </PERSON> <PERSON> Strassman </PERSON> were about to split an atom. Scientists at <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> were about to investigate why a mold called penicillium seemed to kill bacteria. War? Twenty-two at that commencement would die in World War II. But in 1938 a majority of the students approved <PERSON> Neville </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON>'s appeasement of <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>. In a poll, 599 of 974 said they would fight only if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> were invaded. The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> had only 13 of the B-17s that <PERSON> Red </PERSON> <PERSON> Benton </PERSON>, awaiting his diploma alphabetically down front, would one day fly over a beach in <LOCATION> Normandy </LOCATION> named <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>. Behind him tennis star <PERSON> Ramsay </PERSON> <PERSON> Potts </PERSON>, who had been repulsed by <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s `` Mein Kampf,'' would one day interrogate the author's deputy, <PERSON> Hermann </PERSON> <PERSON> Goering </PERSON>, who `` cowered like an animal.'' <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> had not then learned war, not even Dr. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>. When <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Read </PERSON> planned a peace strike, the president, a pacifist, said he'd ring the bell emptying the classrooms `` Then it would n't be a strike,'' Read protested. `` It'd be a better strike,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> and rang the bell. But Dr. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> knew other things. When a faculty member dined with a black radical in <LOCATION> Raleigh </LOCATION>, some on the all-white campus called for his dismissal. `` If a professor has to go on a charge of eating with another human being, then I will go first,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, doctor of philosophy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` We inherited a lemon and made lemonade.'' _ <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavin </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavin </PERSON>: Family lost farm to Depression ... arrived UNC with $ 1.05 in pocket: three Indian head pennies, two Lincolns, the rest silver coins, none a quarter ... lived under football stadium, later $ 5-a-month attic ... raked leaves, cut grass, stoked furnaces to send home $ 5 to $ 10 a month to help three sisters through business course ... now owns lucrative business machine dealership ... two-term mayor of <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION> ... jogger 53 years ... married secretary of prospective employer, who was only hiring Phi Betas ... urged boss to take a chance on poor boy who worked way through ... named a son for <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> ... drives Jeep Wagoneer, wife <PERSON> Chevy </PERSON>, instead of Cadillacs once dreamed of ... `` Material things are not as important as I once thought.''
</TEXT>
