<HEAD>London Shares Off 8.7 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> stock exchange moved lower Tuesday as the market pulled back from Monday's 13.5-point advance. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange index of 100 selected stocks was off 8.7 points, or 0.5 percent at 1,824.0 at midday. Trading volume was a modest 305.8 million shares, compared with 192.5 million shares the same time Monday. `` There is n't enough in this market to shove <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> prices further forward at this stage,'' said <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, chief equity strategist at <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoete </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wedd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>. Market players were still dubious that last week's 114.86-point surge on Wall Street could be sustained That was the biggest point gain on record for a calendar week. Monday's 3.91-point rise in the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average to 2,075.21 did n't convince many skeptics. `` There are a lot of people who feel that Wall Street's rise last week was fairly frothy and premature,'' another equity analyst said, adding that most European equity markets have adopted a wait-and-see attitude in order to get a better handle on the outlook for inflation and interest rate movements. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> exchange remains highly vulnerable to Wall Street's movements. `` Sentiment is such that if Wall Street gets knocked on the head at any stage, so could we get bumped at any time,'' he said.
</TEXT>
