<HEAD>Japanese Exports to U.S. Fall 20 Percent in April</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Exports of Japanese cars and trucks to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> fell a steep 20.3 percent in April, the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said. The association attributed the decline to a drop in sales of Japanese models and an increase in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production by Japanese automakers. <ORGANIZATION> JAMA </ORGANIZATION> said Japanese automakers sent 274,162 cars and trucks to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in April, the latest month for which statistics are available. That was down from 344,068 in the same month last year. For the first four months of 1988, combined car and truck exports are down 14.5 percent from the comparable period in 1987. While Japanese exports have fallen, the Big Three domestic automakers increased their market share. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> have picked up a combined 3.2 points of market share in the car and truck market so far this year. The decline in the value of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar versus the Japanese yen has forced Japanese automakers to raise prices to the point where many Japanese vehicles are more expensive than comparable American-made vehicles. Japanese automakers began May with a 66-day supply of cars and trucks in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, up from a 58-day supply at the same time last year, according to the industry statistical journal <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s Automotive Reports
</TEXT>
