<HEAD>Interest Rates Dip on Short-Term Treasury Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities fell in the latest auction to the lowest level in two weeks. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 6.4 billion in three-month bills Monday at an average discount rate of 6.44 percent, down from 6.53 percent last week. Another $ 6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 6.72 percent, down from 6.83 percent last week. The rates were the lowest since May 23 when three-month bills sold for 6.34 percent and six-month bills averaged 6.71 percent. The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 6.64 percent for three-month bills with a $ 10,000 bill selling for $ 9,837.20 and 7.05 percent for a six-month bill selling for $ 9,660.30. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said the average yield for one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages rose to 7.59 percent last week from 7.58 percent the previous week.
