<HEAD>Foley's Laying Off 5 Percent of Work Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> is laying off 5 percent of its system-wide work force, some 800 employees, in an effort to pare costs, company officials said. <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s, taken over last month by <ORGANIZATION> May </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday the layoffs will affect executives as well as hourly workers. `` It's an attempt to get our operating costs down,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s vice president of public affairs. <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s, which has 39 stores in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, employs about 16,000 workers. May, the nation's seventh-largest retailer, bought <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s and 18 <ORGANIZATION> Filene </ORGANIZATION>'s stores from <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> last month after <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> took control of <PERSON> Federated </PERSON>. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Kristiansen </PERSON>, a retailing analyst with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said May is known for tough expense controls. `` Senior management is closely involved with the divisions,'' she said. May spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> has said May does not plan to close any <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s stores. Last year, <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s merged with another Federated store, <PERSON> Sanger-Harris </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, resulting in the loss of 200 workers in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>.
