<HEAD>Griffin Begins Tender Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> began a tender offer Tuesday for Class A shares of <ORGANIZATION> Resorts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the casino company he is splitting up with developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>. The offer, being made by <ORGANIZATION> Griffco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acquisition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, will pay shareholders $ 36 a share and expires at midnight EDT July 5. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>, the TV talk-show host turned investor, will pay approximately $ 300 million for the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, company, which is controlled by <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>. Using his profits from the deal and other funds, <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> will buy back the company's unfinished crown jewel, the vast Taj Mahal casino in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, for $ 230 million. The agreement calls for <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, Resorts' chairman, to get a total of $ 160 million _ $ 135 a share, or about $ 100 million _ for his Class B shares, and $ 60 million to terminate his management contract. The Class B shares, which carry special voting rights, give him 88 percent control of the company. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> first offered to buy Resorts on March 17 for $ 35 a share. The tender offer culminates a long series of on-again, off-again negotiations.
