<HEAD>Joseph Gallo Elected Wine Institute Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> has been elected chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Wine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, becoming the third member of his family to head the trade group. <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>, 47, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Modesto </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> E. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; J. Gallo Winery, was elected at the institute's annual meeting on Monday. His father, <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON>, was chairman in 1954-55 and again in 1957-58. His cousin, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON>, was chairman in 1977-1978. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Luca </PERSON> continues as <ORGANIZATION> Wine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> president. <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> predicted a 50 percent increase in wine exports for the year, compared to a 65 percent increase last year. He said first-quarter exports of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> wine reached 3.8 million gallons, up 94 percent from a year ago. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> led first quarter export with shipments of more than a million gallons, more than double last year's level.
