<HEAD>Steel Output Fell 2.5 Percent in Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Steel production fell to 1.969 million tons in the week ended June 4, a decrease of 2.5 percent from the previous week's 2.019 million tons, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday. The industry's production amounted to 91.9 percent of capacity during the week, compared with 94.2 percent in the previous week. Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at 45.538 million net tons, an increase of 24.2 percent from the 35.045 million net tons in the previous year. Production so far this year used 91.1 percent of capacity, compared with 73.5 percent a year earlier. Net tonnage by district for the week ended June 4: <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, 280,000; <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, 204,000; <LOCATION> Youngstown </LOCATION>, 129,000; <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION>, 162,000; <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, 160,000; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, 533,000; <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, 183,000; Southern, 218,000; and Western, 100,000.
</TEXT>
