<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorneys for the former president of <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nutrition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, who was convicted of distributing phony apple juice, have asked that their client be ordered to speak to business students about his mistakes as an alternative to a prison term. <PERSON> Niels </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON> was found guilty Feb. 17 of 351 counts of violating the federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act. Each count carries a possible three-year prison term and a $ 10,000 fine. <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON> and a co-defendant, former Beech-Nut Vice President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lavery </PERSON>, are scheduled to be sentenced Friday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lavery </PERSON> was found guilty of 429 counts of violating the same act, along with 18 counts of mail fraud and one count of conspiracy. <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON>'s attorneys said in a presentencing memorandum, `` Business students undoubtedly hear this principle regularly in their ethics classes. But the impact of the message would be far clearer coming from <PERSON> Niels </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON>, whose career has been shattered because he did not heed it, than it could ever be coming from a textbook or a professor.'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON>, the lead prosecutor in the case, said the government's sentencing recommendations would be made public at the sentencing hearing. He declined comment on the memorandum. <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> from April 1981 until shortly before his indictment in November 1986, said in his defense during the trial he did not know about the distribution of flavored sugar water as juice until June 25, 1982. After that date, <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON> said, he relied on the advice of four attorneys in allowing continued distribution of the phony juice. According to the government, the product contained little or no apple juice. <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, is a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Nestle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>.
