<HEAD>FDA To Ban 4 Color Additives Used in Cosmetics, Drugs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is planning to ban four color additives used in cosmetics and drugs because they may cause cancer. Officials announced Monday that the additives _ red dyes Nos. 8, 9 and 19, and orange dye No. 17 _ will be banned beginning July 15. The announcement followed an April 18 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision in which the high court refused to let the government approve the use of color additives that pose a minimal risk of causing cancer. The court rejected arguments by the cosmetics industry that safe substances are being forced off the market. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> let stand a ruling last October by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here that federal law prohibits the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> from approving use of red dye No. 19 and orange dye No. 17 even though the cancer risks are `` trivial.'' Government researchers, citing tests with laboratory animals, said the lifetime use of a product with orange dye No. 17 poses a cancer risk of one in 19 billion, and for red dye No. 19 one in nine million. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said the threat from each use was `` so trivial as to be effectively no risk.'' The appeals court gave a strict interpretation to a 1960 federal law that prohibits <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> approval for any color additive `` found ... to induce cancer in man or animal.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON>, a lawyer for the activist consumer group <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION>, said the decision was important because the dyes offer no health benefit and some cancers will be prevented. `` For cosmetics, it may mean there a few shades of lipstick that will be lost. I think that will make no difference to people,'' he said. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Barton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutt </PERSON>, a lawyer representing the Cosmetics, <ORGANIZATION> Toiletries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fragrances </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the decision was a disappointment but that it was `` more important as a symbol than in terms of its specific impact.''
