<HEAD>Brokers Boycott Stock Exchange To Protest Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Indian stock brokers on Tuesday boycotted trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Bombay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> to protest violence on the trading floor a day earlier. The exchange, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s largest, was officially open, but no transactions were reported. The exchange was shut down Monday afternoon after disgruntled exchange workers agitating for higher pay attacked brokers on the trading floor. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said that 12 brokers were injured in the melee. The workers had staged a one-day strike May 9 to underscore their demand for pay increases. The market, in the doldrums for months, has been recovering in recent weeks following widespread approval of the Indian government's 1988-89 budget and its new import-export policy, which liberalizes trade regulations for many industries.
