<NOTE>$adv 11</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 11-12 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>North Dakota Company Making Mark In Message Board Industry</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF MEYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAYVILLE, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A rural <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> factory is making it easier to locate baggage at busy airports, place bets at <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> casinos and even find love in a bustling East Coast singles bar. <ORGANIZATION> Northstar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> makes computerized indoor message boards and signs and is winning acceptance as one of the leaders in the industry. `` We really feel we're the Cadillac of the business,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Northstar </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Larson </PERSON>. `` That's what we're shooting for.'' <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> declines to disclose the 9-year-old company's sales figures but said they have grown by 20 percent to 30 percent a year since it was founded. He predicts that the light-emitting diode industry in five years should reach $ 200 million in sales, and he believes <ORGANIZATION> Northstar </ORGANIZATION> will capture up to 20 percent of the market. `` The opportunities are just unlimited,'' said <PERSON> Larson </PERSON>. The industry is relatively new. About six <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies are manufacturing electronic message systems, and most are less than a decade old. <ORGANIZATION> Northstar </ORGANIZATION> started in 1979 with five products. It now offers more than 30, and is doing more custom design work, said <PERSON> Larson </PERSON>, who joined the company in 1980 and became president in 1982. <ORGANIZATION> Northstar </ORGANIZATION>'s message boards can be programmed for hundreds of different messages from a computer keyboard. The messages can be programmed to run laterally or up and down and can be accompanied by graphics or animation. The message boards can be custom-built to any specifications, but many of the signs come with letters about 7 inches to 8 inches high, <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> said. The boards are generally long but only about as deep as the letters. The signs are made up of hundreds of bulbs -LRB- most come with red bulbs -RRB- which light up according to a computer command to form messages. `` Specialized software is where the future lies,'' said <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>, vice president and national sales manager and the last of <ORGANIZATION> Northstar </ORGANIZATION>'s three founders still with the company. <ORGANIZATION> Northstar </ORGANIZATION> was founded by two <LOCATION> Mayville </LOCATION> men, <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Beck </PERSON>, and a Chicago-based computer consultant, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON>, who saw an untapped market for electronic message systems. The company operates out of a 5,000-square-foot plant located between <LOCATION> Mayville </LOCATION>, population 2,255, and <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, population 627, about 55 miles north of <LOCATION> Fargo </LOCATION>, N.D. The plant employs 22 people full-time, and another dozen part-timers are on the payroll. In 1986, <ORGANIZATION> Northstar </ORGANIZATION> merged with <ORGANIZATION> Lexicon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City-based </LOCATION> company that made computer software. The company has placed boards in airports, casinos, hospitals, restaurants, bars, bowling alleys, financial institutions and schools nationwide. <ORGANIZATION> Northstar </ORGANIZATION> boards flash instant odds on sporting events at <PERSON> Caesar </PERSON>'s Palace in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Harrah </PERSON>'s in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> Several mid-size airports use the boards to help travelers locate baggage and boarding areas. The company also has completed a deal with the <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> said. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Northstar </ORGANIZATION> has developed what it believes to be the first electronic display cardiac alert system in the nation, <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> said. The system, which has been in use at the <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> for four years, allows medical personnel to alert 27 critical areas of the hospital simultaneously during an emergency involving a heart patient, he says. Looking to the future, company officials see its message boards used as promotional devices on city buses, subway cars and pay-telephones. Company officials believe the airport industry provides the greatest potential, and <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> said he is already working on more projects with major airports around the country. One of the most unusual uses of the company's message boards has been in a game called Selectrocution played in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> singles bars. In the game, bar patrons use a message board to make acquaintances. The game ends with the patrons being ranked for desirability by others in the bar and matched by computer at evening's end with anyone expressing mutual interest. With bids out on more than $ 16 million worth of projects and several others already in the works, <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> feels the future holds promise for his company. `` Our products are applicable in so many areas it's hard to narrow the scope to areas that will have the greatest impact,'' <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> said. `` We're trying to look at key ... markets where we can concentrate and do a good job.''
