<HEAD>Cooler Makers Offer New Ad Approaches, Flavors</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cooler makers are putting on a new face this summer as they try to inspire fresh interest in a beverage category whose torrid growth pace slowed markedly last year. The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Cooler beach party is history. So is the Sun Country cooler spokesbear. And actor <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> is missing from the action in new ads for <ORGANIZATION> Seagram </ORGANIZATION>'s Wine Coolers. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> are still pitching <ORGANIZATION> Bartles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Jaymes </PERSON> coolers, but it is uncertain who is going to be dreaming up new commercials for the folksy pair since the ad agency that created the brand's fictional founding fathers quit. Something else is missing _ the fruit pulp that category pioneer <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Cooler had once brandished as evidence that it was `` the real stuff.'' But the cooler makers are trying to liven things up with new flavors that they hope will get people to try their first cooler or give them another try. <ORGANIZATION> Seagram </ORGANIZATION>'s, the category leader, plans eight flavors this year, up from six last year. <ORGANIZATION> Bartles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Jaymes </PERSON> has doubled its list to four. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Cooler has five flavors, up from four a year ago. The big question facing the industry is whether coolers are a sustainable segment of the alcoholic beverage market or just a fad. Cooler sales tailed off in the second half of last summer, prompting some analysts to speculate that consumers had tired of the sweet-tasting concoctions of fruit juice, alcohol and water and were moving on to other drinks. According to Impact, a publication of <ORGANIZATION> M. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shanken </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> that tracks the wine business, cooler shipments grew only 6 percent to an estimated 72.6 million cases in 1987. Industry executives said at an average price of about $ 3.50 for a four-pack, that put the retail value of the category at about $ 1.5 billion. But the 1987 growth rate was well below that in each of the previous three years in which the category rocketed from a few million cases in 1983. Impact said the category grew 65 percent in 1986 after tripling the previous year and soaring more than fivefold in 1984 when <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Cooler first encountered serious competition. Analysts said a slowdown in such growth was inevitable. `` Maybe for some people it was a fad,'' said <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Fredrikson </PERSON>, president of <LOCATION> Gomberg </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Fredrikson </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, wine industry consultants in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` But we believe there are hard-core wine-cooler drinkers out there who will continue to drink these products.'' <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shanken </PERSON>, editor and publisher of Impact, said he also thought the category would survive and recently predicted it would amount to 133 million cases annually by the year 2000. They each cited the category's appeal to women drinkers and others who prefer an light-alcohol alternative to beer. The short-term outlook is unclear, however. <PERSON> Shanken </PERSON> refused to estimate growth prospects for 1988 and <PERSON> Fredrikson </PERSON> said the market may be flat. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Slone </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Beverage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, a trade publisher, said, `` A lot of people have their fingers crossed, but we have n't seen any upturn in that market yet. Among retailers, there is no expectation of any meaningful growth this year.'' <ORGANIZATION> Seagram </ORGANIZATION>'s Wine Coolers, from <ORGANIZATION> Seagram </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beverage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, nosed ahead of <ORGANIZATION> Bartles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Jaymes </PERSON> from <ORGANIZATION> E. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; J. Gallo Winery of <LOCATION> Modesto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, last year, according to Impact. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Cooler from <ORGANIZATION> Brown-Forman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beverage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION> was third, followed by <PERSON> Sun </PERSON> <PERSON> Country </PERSON>, made by <ORGANIZATION> Canandaigua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of a town by that name in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Seagram </ORGANIZATION> ended its two-year association with <PERSON> Willis </PERSON>, the star of the television series `` Moonlighting,'' by mutual agreement this year, said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Taxel </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Seagram </ORGANIZATION> executive. He said <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> helped <ORGANIZATION> Seagram </ORGANIZATION> `` get to where we are in the market, but our needs now are more complex.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> Seagram </ORGANIZATION> will use a series of celebrities for different flavors of its coolers, including its new Lime Mist and <ORGANIZATION> Seagram </ORGANIZATION>'s Extra New ads aired so far have featured actors <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Guttenberg </PERSON>, <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrelson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Archer </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Bartles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Jaymes </PERSON> introduced a berry flavor in January and a new peach cooler in April which, for the first time, was heralded in an ad featuring <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> and Ed that was not created by <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>'s longtime agency, <ORGANIZATION> Hal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Riney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Partners of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Riney </PERSON> resigned last December, and <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> declined to discuss when a new fulltime agency may be retained. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Cooler had put the pulp in its citrus and orange coolers from the start in the early 1980s to make them look like the drinks that the today's coolers descended from _ mixtures of fruit juice and wine poured over huge blocks of ice in tubs on <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s beaches in the 1960s. Its ads once featured songs from the era, like `` <PERSON> Louie </PERSON>, <PERSON> Louie </PERSON>'' and `` The Bird is the Word.'' But both the beach party scenes and the'60s classics are gone from the new ads that use special effects to do things like transform a cherry into a bottle of its new Wild Cherry Splash flavor. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Shastid </PERSON>, an executive at <ORGANIZATION> Brown-Forman </ORGANIZATION>, said that while pulp had been an effective early addition to the drinks, consumers now realize coolers contain real fruit juice and prefer coolers without pulp. Sun Country dumped the pulp from its flavors, too, saying consumers were turned off by sediment at the bottom of the bottle. It has also retired the ad approach that used celebrities in polar bear costumes to pitch its drink, which now comes in eight flavors, up from six. The steamy ads for its new <LOCATION> Strawberry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Blush </LOCATION> and Wild Jamaican Rum-Flavored wine coolers made the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> and CBS networks blush. Executives demanded revisions in the ads that show scantily-dressed men and women looking for relief from the heat, and Sun Country complied. <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which entered the cooler market with <LOCATION> Matilda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> last fall, recently introduced its second flavor. Its ads pitch the only non-carbonated cooler among the majors as a drink from <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. It is undaunted that another brewer, <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, abandoned the cooler market by discontinuing its <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> brand last year. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Boykin </PERSON>, brand manager for <LOCATION> Matilda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> is convinced of the longterm potential of the market. `` We think we can be one of the key players in the category,'' he said.
