<HEAD>West Europeans Show More Tangible Signs of Greater Unity in EEC</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Accompanying items are BC-EEC-Unity-Members and
BC-EEC-Unity-Movers. Also moved on general news wires.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, cars carry the first `` European'' license plates, featuring a replica of a blue-and-yellow European flag. At a rural train stop in northern <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> a new welcoming sign not only says the town is <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> but that <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> is a member of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, or Common Market. In the Dutch town of Sint-Oedenrode a furniture-manufacturing plant flies the same flag that is on the <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>'s license plates, and a sticker on a restaurant window in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, site of <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> headquarters, says: `` My country: <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' Across much of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> outward signs are multiplying that the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> is drawing wider public interest in its quest to create a true community of nations and, in the view of proponents, gain greater influence on international economic and political matters. Already the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> is in conflict with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> on some economic issues, and business competition with these two economic powerhouses and other Western allies is growing in many areas. The most recent dispute with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is over <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> farm subsidies and their effects on American farmers. At the same time, the 12-nation community has been improving trade ties with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the communist <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc _ even more so than with its Western allies. While the 31-year-old organization still is far from its goal of fully weaving together the economic, social and political fabric of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the integration process in recent years has reached a new plateau, one from which ordinary citizens can feel involved. The community has created its own currency, the European currency unit -LRB- ECU -RRB-, for bookkeeping purposes but eventually hopes to circulate the currency for common use among its people. To promote that idea, the winner of an annual EEC-sponsored tennis tournament is paid in an ECU check which can be cashed for another EEC national currency. It's still not clear how far the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> can go with its drive for greater European unity. Some of its members, including <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, show little desire to go beyond the creation of a simple common market in which goods and people can move freely across national frontiers. Others are dedicated to a grander goal: a <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> with a single political identity, or, as its founders liked to put it, a <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Whatever the approach, the pool of money available for joint spending is limited. The members devote less than 2 percent of their national incomes to the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> budget, which this year totals $ 55 billion. Even the more modest goal of ending national barriers to trade has been beyond the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s reach. Some European leaders say this is the organization's most damning failure, although most believe the bloc will meet its latest self-imposed deadline of 1992 for removing these barriers. An <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> study published in May said creation of a genuine common market by 1992 would mean a 4.5 percent boost in economic growth for the region, a 6 percent drop in consumer prices and 1.8 million new jobs. The study said the European economy could save as much as $ 320 billion over an unspecified `` medium term'' by achieving an integrated market. Despite its slightly blurred vision of the future, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> appears to have found new success in persuading people that the slow, tedious process of European integration is more than a bureaucratic exercise. Opinion polls show a slight increase in recent years in public support for the idea of European unification, although most people still have only a vague notion of what the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> is and how it operates. A poll of people in all member nations late last year indicated that 85 percent thought their country's membership in the group was a good thing. A 1983 poll put the figure at 79 percent, and in 1980 it was 76 percent. In some ways the effort to make people feel attached to the aims and affairs of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> is seen by its leaders as their most important task. In the early years of this decade, the Common Market was mired in a seemingly endless dispute over internal finances. Decisions on other matters fell far behind schedule. Nothing seemed to be getting done, and all the while people saw high inflation and growing unemployment. This was more than just another weak moment for an organization that had survived many while remaining largely on track. A turnaround began in June 1984. At a meeting in the 16th century <ORGANIZATION> Fontainebleau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chateau </ORGANIZATION> outside <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> government leaders resolved their budget wrangle, although other money problems cropped up later. Of possibly more lasting significance was a decision at that summit meeting to launch what was called a `` People's <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'' campaign. The leaders at <LOCATION> Fontainebleau </LOCATION> recognized that the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s problems went deeper than the money debate. They saw a need to make the whole integration process appear relevant to individual citizens, to make people believe that the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s aspirations were bound up with their own. `` We're putting <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> back in gear,'' <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorn </PERSON>, then the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s chief executive, said when the Fontainebleau Accords were announced.
</TEXT>
