<HEAD>European Experts Meet on Pollution Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARLSKRONA, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Experts from eastern and western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> met in this port city Tuesday in an attempt to sort out the pollution problems that are plaguing the Baltic and the North seas. A carpet of algae spread in recent weeks along the <LOCATION> Norwegian </LOCATION> and Swedish coasts, killing farm trout and salmon worth millions of dollars and causing unknown damage to wild fish. An epidemic of a herpes virus has killed hundreds of seals in Danish and German waters this spring. Pollution from farms, sewers and industry was suspected in both cases. About 175 delegates from <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> were attending the three-day meeting, said spokesman <PERSON> Torsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Wikstrom </PERSON>. The timing of the conference, coinciding with the algae plague, `` was not meant that way,'' said <PERSON> Wikstrom </PERSON>. But he said the algae was a main topic on the first day of talks. Farmers from all countries represented have been blamed for heavy use of fertilizers, which eventually find their way to the seas, and some municipal governments will face costly outlays for better sewage treatment if the seas are to be cleaned up. <PERSON> Harald </PERSON> <PERSON> Velner </PERSON>, executive secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Helsinki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, singled out the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> as major polluters. But <PERSON> Wikstrom </PERSON> said the meeting has mostly been free of recriminations. The delegates included local, regional and national politicians as well as marine experts
