<HEAD>Court Sets Aside Injunction in Eastern Shuttle Sale</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf with comment; also moved general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court today set aside a contempt of court order against <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and an injunction barring the company from selling its Northeast shuttle to another subsidiary of its parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here ruled that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> failed to make proper factual findings when he held <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> in contempt for taking steps to sell the profitable <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shuttle </ORGANIZATION> to a newly created subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>. The deal was challenged by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>, which contended the sale would violate the terms of a July, 1987 injunction that <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> had issued in another labor dispute involving Eastern. The <ORGANIZATION> IAM </ORGANIZATION>, which represents 13,000 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> employees, contends that <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> is trying to break up the airlines' various components to weaken the power of the unions at the financially troubled carrier, which <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> purchased in 1986. A unanimous three-judge panel dissolved the injunction issued by <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> that bars Eastern from proceeding with plans to sell the <LOCATION> Boston-to-New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York-to-Washington </LOCATION> shuttle to another subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> for $ 225 million. It also set aside the modified injunction <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> issued barring the sale, but gave the union 10 days to seek a temporary restraining order to stop the deal. The court directed <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> to hold a factual hearing to determine if an injunction is warranted. The court, in an opinion by Judge <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, held that the July 1987 injunction <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> issued barring Eastern from transferring 6,000 ground-crew workers into a subsidiary called Airport Ground Services did not prohibit the shuttle deal. Thus Eastern could not be held in contempt of the 1987 order for taking steps to transfer ownership of the shuttle. `` In issuing the March order, the district court did not weigh the tradiitonal equitable criteria, nor did it make factual findings, necessary to support the issuance of a new or modified injunction,'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> wrote in an opinion joined by Judges <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oberdorfer </PERSON>. `` We appreciate the district court's concern that <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement of the shuttle deal may have suggested a disregard for the spirit of the July injunction,'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> wrote `` Nonetheless, this is an insufficient basis upon which to rest a finding of contempt where the district court has issued a new or modified injunction.'' <ORGANIZATION> IAM </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Conley </PERSON> said the union had no immediate comment because its lawyers had not yet studied the decision. Eastern spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said `` we are pleased with the decision and are studying its implications.''
