   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan is chipping away at its mammoth trade surplus</FIRST>
<SECOND>y expanding imports and overseas investment but the United States</SECOND>
<TEXT>
 has yet to adequately address its own foreign trade imbalance, the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. In a report on <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s foreign trade in 1987, <ORGANIZATION> MITI </ORGANIZATION> said structural changes in the country's economy, combined with the yen's appreciation against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar, have led to increased imports and a slowing of growth in exports `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s industrial structure is becoming geared to domestic demand,'' said <PERSON> Atsushi </PERSON> <PERSON> Oi </PERSON>, director of the ministry's <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>. `` Manufactured imports are increasing rapidly and the distribution system is undergoing a change.'' Imports of manufactured goods rose to $ 73.9 billion in fiscal 1987 from $ 55.2 billion in fiscal 1986, fueled primarily by the rapid appreciation of the Japanese yen, according to government statistics. But the report warned that the budget and trade deficits of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, as well as other international imbalances, `` are having a dampening influence on trade and investment by causing exchange rate fluctuations and destabilizing market prices.'' Some economists say the period of sharp reductions in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus is at an end While the surplus has been declining compared with last year's levels, the seasonally adjusted trade surplus has lately been increasing from month to month. <PERSON> Oi </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could reduce its trade deficit by slashing runaway consumer demand, expanding production facilities and revamping its export policy. The ministry report urged major industrial countries to coordinate their economic policies more closely in light of today's rising economic interdependence `` International policy coordination is essential to the effective resolution of imbalances,'' said Oi, whose office compiled the report, which has been issued annually since 1949. Finance Minister <PERSON> Kiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> said Tuesday that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will fall from the present 40 percent of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s total exports to 25 to 30 percent of total exports He did not predict how long it would take for that to happen. Spurred by the rapid rise in the value of the yen, imports of consumer goods from the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> rose by 26.3 percent in 1987 over the previous year, the trade ministry said. Those from the newly industrialized countries of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> soared by 50.3 percent in the same period, according to the trade report. By comparison, imports of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumer goods rose only 8.4 percent. Since early 1985, the yen has risen by more than 100 percent against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar, making Japanese exports more expensive overseas but boosting <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s import buying power. <PERSON> Oi </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is prepared to import more manufactured goods from <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> nations and step up direct investment in the region. He said <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s newly industrialized countries have depended on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market for their development, `` but it will be difficult to continue to depend on exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' To offset the burden on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was prepared to help by absorbing more Asian products and offering technological and economic assistance, as well as stepping up direct investment, he said.
