<FIRST>r f AM-ChildLabor     06-07 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Labor,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>ILO: Unions, Governments Do Little Against Child Labor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Illegal exploitation of child workers is widespread in much of the Third World, and most national trade unions do little to combat it, according to a report released Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. The report by the Geneva-based group said some governments fail to enforce bans against child labor and even facilitate exploitation because industries that employ children can be important earners of foreign exchange. Some experts cited in the report estimate that at least 100 million boys and girls are employed worldwide, many of them younger than 10 years old and many unpaid. Those who are paid for their work `` rarely receive an income even approaching the minimum wage,'' the survey said. `` They receive no fringe benefits, insurance or social security payments ... child workers are the lowest paid but work the longest hours.'' The 226-page report noted that such conditions give employers a competitive advantage abroad. Regional studies included in the report said some exporters in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> would rather cease trading than replace children with adult labor because of the cost of the switch. The report deplored the `` almost total absence of initiatives by national workers' organizations in the campaign against child labor.'' `` Because the exploitation of child workers can be a threat to their economic interest and because it constitutes a violation of the rights and dignity for which labor has campaigned all along, workers' organizations have a particular obligation to promote and assist in the campaign against child labor,'' the report said. Recent efforts by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unions </ORGANIZATION> and by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are the `` almost sole exceptions,'' the report said. Case studies in the report acknowledged efforts made in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and said child labor was virtually eliminated in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> following improvements in social security benefits and education policy. But the report said that in much of the Third World, child labor continues to be `` widely prevalent _ in agriculture, industry, and services _ despite national legislation prohibiting it.'' Payment in many industries is made upon completion of a specified task or period, it said. In Peruvian gold mines and in deep sea fishing operations off the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, medicines, supplementary food, and working days lost because of illness are deducted from the pay, according to the report. Children, more likely to suffer occupational injuries, may be indebted to the employer at the end of the contract. Fifteen years ago, the confederation set a mimimum age of 12 or 13 for `` light work.'' But a study on child labor in the quarries and brickyards of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> found the majority of the children working there started `` even before they were eight years old,'' the report said. The report said that in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, family labor involved around 90 percent of all children between six and 15 years of age and was common in both rural and urban areas in a large variety of tasks, from washing clothes to the sale of crops on local markets.
</TEXT>
