<HEAD>Amtrak Chairman Confident Railroad Will Survive</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday he is confident the passenger railroad will survive and gain the support of the next president, whether Democrat or Republican. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has rejected ... proposals to terminate <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> for four successive years,'' <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Claytor </PERSON> told reporters, referring to repeated attempts by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to end federal subsidies for the railroad. <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> is expected to get about $ 580 million in federal money next year but will cover two-thirds of its operating costs through various revenue sources, <PERSON> Claytor </PERSON> said. Only 48 percent of the rail system's costs were covered by revenues in 1981, he said. The administration repeatedly has called for an end to federal subsidies for <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION>, but each time <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has continue to provide the rail system with reduced amounts of money. `` Today ... things are looking better,'' said <PERSON> Claytor </PERSON>, expressing optimism about getting the additional federal funds in future years that will allow <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> to begin expanding its operations. He said he expects either Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> or Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to support <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> if elected president, although <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has yet to say specifically whether he would favor increased funding for the railroad. <PERSON> Claytor </PERSON> said his key objective is to have both the Democratic and Republican parties go on record as supporting the continuing need for a national passenger rail system. `` I'm optimistic this will be the position of a new administration, whether <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> or Democratic,'' he said. While in recent years <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> has battled for its survival, <PERSON> Claytor </PERSON> talked during a session with reporters at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> about expanding services in the years to come. `` The principal problem we see ahead is capacity. ... On weekends and hoidays we do n't have the equipment to accommodate peak loads on our unreserved <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corridor </ORGANIZATION> trains'' between <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, he said. <PERSON> Claytor </PERSON> said that for the first time in recent years <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> has been on firm enough footing politically to obtain financing for new locomotives and train cars. He said <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> has arranged financing for the purchase of 18 new diesel and electric locomotives and up to 100 new coach cars. `` The locomotives are now being delivered and the first 50 coaches will be on hand in 12 to 15 months,'' he said.
