<HEAD>Government Announces Sale of State-Owned Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said Tuesday that it would offer the state-owned bank, <ORGANIZATION> Girobank </ORGANIZATION>, for sale to a financial institution. <ORGANIZATION> Girobank </ORGANIZATION>, formally National Giro, is <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s sixth-largest bank. It was set up in 1968 to cater to the banking needs of working-class Britons and is now part of the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>. Industry Minister <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> announced the government's latest privatization in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION>, saying the bank `` now needs to expand vigorously. The sale of the bank, which analysts said could raise 300 million pounds, or about $ 543 million, is expected to take place by the end of the year. Merchant bankers will be in charge of assessing the bids for <ORGANIZATION> Girobank </ORGANIZATION> under the guidance of the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>. The bank, which has about 2.5 million customers, had pretax profit last year of 23.1 million British pounds, or about $ 42 million, on revenue of 328 million pounds, or $ 594 million. `` It will ... be important to safeguard close links between <ORGANIZATION> Girobank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> counters,'' <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> said. Conservative Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> has previously ruled out the privatization of the nation's mail delivery service, but not of other postal operations. In addition to the bank and the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> also oversees a subsidiary which runs the counters where stamps are sold, parcels weighed and banking services provided. Opposition lawmaker <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Benn </PERSON>, who as <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> government Postmaster General launched <ORGANIZATION> Girobank </ORGANIZATION> 22 years ago, said the privatization of the bank was a `` naked act of plunder'' of a public asset which had been `` wildly successful''. Although the offer price will be a major factor in deciding who takes over the bank, it will not simply be sold to the highest bidder, <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> said. The government will also look at the bidders' plans for developing the bank, the impact of the sale on the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> and other factors, he said. <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> signaled government opposition to a takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Girobank </ORGANIZATION> by any of the `` Big Four'' commercial banking companies: <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Westminster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lloyds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Girobank </ORGANIZATION> is primarily used as a savings bank by retired and poor people who do n't need all the services of a retail bank. <ORGANIZATION> Girobank </ORGANIZATION> issues checks and has post office hours, which are longer than bank hours. It is also used to pay gas, electricity and other bills, as well as to wire money within <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and abroad. <ORGANIZATION> Girobank </ORGANIZATION> has reached a new five-year contract with the counters subsidiary through which it operates, <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> said. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> has sold off billions of pounds worth of state-owned assets, primarily through the sale of shares to the public, as a way of promoting capitalism in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Companies sold off include <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, the phone company which also used to be run by the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>.
