<HEAD>Jury Begins Deliberations In Cigarette Liability Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after the 4th to UPDATE with jurors recessed
for night after four hours; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Deliberations began Tuesday in the case of a widower suing three tobacco companies over the lung-cancer death of his wife, who smoked cigarettes for 40 years. The verdict in the 5-year-old case _ one of a dozen cigarette liability cases ever to go to a jury _ could maintain the $ 22 billion industry's unbeaten record in such suits or grant the first damages paid to smokers or their relatives. The six-person jury contains one smoker, two former smokers and three people who have never smoked. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> read instructions on the law and claims that the panel must consider. <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> told five alternate jurors to remain on hand in case any jurors drop out. The jurors deliberated for more than four hours before being dismissed for the night. The panel must decide charges by <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> that <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> contributed to the death of his 58-year-old wife, <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, in 1984. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> contends the companies misled the public about the dangers of smoking through public relations, advertising and inadequate research. <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> told the jurors they must decide four basic claims: fraudulent misrepresentation and conspiracy to do so against each company, and failure to warn and violation of a warranty against <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION>. The warning and warranty claims apply only to <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> because Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> smoked that company's cigarettes before warning labels were placed on cigarette packages and advertising in 1966. Courts have ruled that the labels pre-empt liability claims after that date. <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> framed the main charge as a claim that the companies `` fraudulently misrepresented material facts to consumers concerning significant health risks associated with cigarette smoking.'' He said the jury has to determine five things _ that before 1966 the company made a false representation; that the company knew the representation was false; that the company meant to deceive people; that Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> believed the representation, justifiably relied on it and was induced to continue smoking; and that the representation was a `` proximate cause'' of her cancer and death. The phrase `` proximate cause'' played a key role in the jury instructions. <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> said the panel has to consider whether the companies' conduct before 1966 was a proximate cause of her smoking, and then whether the smoking was a proximate cause of her death and disease. The legal term means activity that `` naturally and probably led to and might have been expected to'' create the condition alleged, <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> wrote. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> does n't have to prove thatthe companies' conduct was the only or even main reason why she smoked, only that it was a `` substantial contributing factor.
