<HEAD>Universal Banks: The Wave of the Future</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDs grafs 10-14, Later at ... anyone else, to Update with
afternoon developments</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 International bankers and businessmen said Tuesday that the stage was being set for the eventual creation of a universal banking system, which would offer a variety of financial services to customers around the globe. For one thing, regulatory barriers that separated investment and commercial banks, such as the Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, were being abolished or re-examined, <PERSON> Rainer </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gut </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Suisse </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>. He said the bank of the future will have to change its business strategy by becoming more competitive and aggressive. `` In the 1990s, the typical manager in a successful universal bank, will be globally oriented, have a flair for market opportunities, and possess entrepreneurial instincts,'' Gut said in prepared remarks made available to the news media. The three-day monetary conference, in its 34th year, provides leaders of the top commerical banks and corporations in about two dozen countries an opportunity to confer with government officials on topics affecting the world economy and international banking. <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> and other central bankers from abroad were scheduled to attend Wednesday's closed-door session. Much of Tuesday's session focused on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banking system with some conference participants criticizing the inconsistencies between domestic and foreign regulations. `` Effective governance, both domestic and international, has not kept pace,'' <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> told the conference. `` Our sites must be set on achieving an environment in which all types of financial institutions can compete with adequate rules of fair play _ a credible regulatory framework,'' he said. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said all financial institutions should have fair access to the global markets while countries work together to harmonize otherwise outdated regulations. Later, at a media briefing Tuesday, several bankers, including <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's biggest banking company, briefly discussed the level of regulation among global institutions. <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Heldring </PERSON> said big banks that take risks should n't always expect government protection. `` We ultimately could come to a form of Chapter 11'' federal bankruptcy reorganization, <ORGANIZATION> Heldring </ORGANIZATION> said. `` If a bank is too large to fail, it is subject to the risk of becoming an arm of government.'' <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> agreed, `` It makes us more vulnerable to becoming bullied by the regulators.'' He noted that while government regulators look at the role banks play in society, `` the sociology does n't play in the management room. We should be allowed to fail as anyone else.''
</TEXT>
