<SECOND>AM-Electronics Powwow,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Electronics Industry Seeks To Regain Consumer Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electronics industry announced Tuesday it will seek to re-enter the consumer business lost to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> by playing a major role in the projected $ 40 billion world market for a new generation of televisions. Calling the effort to catch up to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in advanced television research a `` last window of opportunity,'' the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said it is forming a task force to explore a possible alliance of industry, government and academia. At a meeting Monday of more than 50 computer, semiconductor and telecommunications industry leaders, government officials and academic researchers, a consensus was reached in five areas: _ The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electronics industry should be in the consumer business _ Advanced television, which is expected to deliver stunningly realistic images and sound, means more to the electronics industry than just re-entering the consumer market _ Advanced television will drive the leading edge technologies, such as advanced semiconductors _ An open system of design should be used rather than one that locks in specific parameters and specific manufacturers _ A broadcast standard should be adopted that is advantageous to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers, broadcasters and consumers `` We found that the implications for ATV -LRB- advanced television -RRB- for our industry and for the economic well-being of the country are pervasive,'' said <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON>, vice president of the 3,500-member <ORGANIZATION> AEA </ORGANIZATION>. `` One point stressed throughout the meeting,'' he said, `` was the non-participation in this market by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electronics industry will mean the loss of our leading edge research and, in turn, our ability to compete in the emerging global marketplace.'' Companies attending the electronics powwow included <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T, <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Micro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Intel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Among the government officials was <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Sikes </PERSON>, assistant secretary of Commerce for communication and information policy. `` We hope this is a catalytic meeting for what is to be done,'' said <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON>, senior vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> AEA </ORGANIZATION>, which hosted the meeting at its headquarters. `` We're talking about how we got to where we are n't,'' he said wryly, `` and finding out where we want to go.'' Where they are n't, he said, is in consumer electronics, a multibillion-dollar industry pioneered by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies but now dominated by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The group Monday talked about whether high-definition television, which the Japanese have been working on for several years, will revolutionize the TV industry and spin off as many other technologies as did videotape and digital recording. `` We're reminding ourselves of the stakes involved,'' <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> said. `` There's a whole lot more involved here than TVs. We're talking about a whole electronics era The tone in the room is leading us to the conclusion it is a revolution in electronics. That's certainly <ORGANIZATION> AEA </ORGANIZATION>'s conclusion.'' Although it is unusual to have competitive companies in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> meet to discuss broad technological ventures, and to have government involved as well, such meetings are common in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` The Japanese have been at it for 20 years, and they're way ahead of us on this technology,'' <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> said.
