<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Payout for Closed Thrifts; U.S. Productivity Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's thrift industry is showing more signs of strain, but the government says the productivity of the nation's work force is still on the rise. Federal regulators announced a record $ 1.35 billion payout to close two insolvent savings institutions Monday. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported a big increase in productivity statistics for the first quarter. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> closed <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diversified </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, both of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, without arranging for a takeover by another institution. Only 10 of 235 failed S & amp; Ls handled since 1981 have been resolved with a straight payoff of depositors. Usually, the bank board pays a bonus to a healthy thrift to buy a sick S & amp; L or arranges to transfer deposits to another institution. But bank board Chairman <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> said the thrifts had little value as going concerns because they had few retail deposits and lacked branch offices. Both also relied on high-cost, short-term deposits arranged through brokers, which they in turn lent out for speculative real estate ventures and other risky investments. The institutions have been insolvent for some time. Regulators took over the management of American Diversified in February 1986 and of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> Savings in January 1987. <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> said the bank board is paying $ 1.14 billion from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to American Diversified depositors, the largest cash payout the agency has ever made. It is covering $ 209 million in deposits at <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> Savings. Deposits up to the insurance limit of $ 100,000 will be available beginning Tuesday. A total of about $ 500,000 in both institutions exceeded the limit. Those depositors will share in liquidation proceeds. In a new economic report, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the nation's efficiency in churning out goods and services improved more than four times more rapidily during the first quarter of 1988 than it did in 1987 But average annualized hourly wage gains of only 3.4 percent failed to put most workers ahead of inflation for the fifth quarter in a row, it said. Not since the spiraling inflation of 1979-81 have workers gone that long without an improvement in their standard of living through wage gains, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>. Productivity among the nation's non-farm businesses increased at an annual rate of 3.6 percent during January through March. Preliminary figures last month had put the improvement at only 0.9 percent. But those earlier figures were issued before the gross national product _ the broadest measure of economic growth _ was revised upward. In another sign of improving economic conditions, the number of Americans late on their mortgage payments fell to the second-lowest level of this decade during the first three months of the year, a trade group of lenders reported. The Mortgage Bankers Association said the number of mortgage payments late by 30 days or more dropped to 4.78 percent of total mortgages in the first quarter, down from 4.95 percent in the last three months of 1987.
</TEXT>
