<HEAD>Bass, Macmillan Move Buyout Battle To The Courtroom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The courtroom is likely to be the scene of the next encounter between <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> billionaire <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the giant publishing company he has offered to buy for $ 1.9 billion, or $ 73 a share. Bass filed a lawsuit Monday after <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> failed to respond to his latest offer, but <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> had already filed its own suit charging Bass with securities laws violations. `` Going to court clearly makes this unfriendly, but it already really was,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorp </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Provident </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. On Wall Street, <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> jumped $ 3.50 a share to $ 75 in trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts were nonplussed by the legal developments and said it is likely the Bass suit will delay the restructuring dividend <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> plans to begin paying shareholders on Friday. The Macmillan board, which rejected <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>'s initial $ 64-a-share offer as inadequate, adopted a plan to split the company's publishing and non-publishing operations into two separate, publicly owned corporations Part of the plan includes paying shareholders a special dividend of $ 52.35 a share. In a suit filed Monday in <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> is seeking to block the company from proceeding with the payout. In what analysts characterized as a further attempt to appease management, Bass alternatively offered to restructure the company along the lines of a plan <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> unveiled last week, but on terms more favorable to shareholders. He is offering a payout of $ 58 a share. Bass representatives made the proposals at a meeting over the weekend with <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON>'s investment bankers and requested a response by noon Monday. But <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> allowed the deadline to tick by, saying in a statement it would consider the proposal `` later in the week.'' In its suit filed Monday morning in federal court for the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> charged <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> with `` repeated filing and public dissemination of misleading statements ... in order to engage in creeping tender offers ...'' The suit further claims that the defendants were `` so anxious to hide their intent, to deceive <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> and its shareholders, and to manipulate the market in <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> shares, that on or about Oct. 13, 1987, the broker who was placing defendants' orders for <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> shares falsely stated that he was acting on behalf of <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> itself.'' The Bass group holds about 9.1 percent of <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON>'s roughly 26 million outstanding shares. The stake was built between August 1987 and last month, according to the lawsuit. Neither side would comment further on the latest developments. Analysts had predicted the battle would move to the courtroom. `` It was a logical reaction for both sides to what was going on,'' said <PERSON> Berk </PERSON> <PERSON> Boksen </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Raymond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>. There has been considerable speculation that a third party might surface, and that remains a possibility, analysts say. `` But with both Bass and <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> putting short deadlines, it puts a squeeze on anybody new coming in,'' <PERSON> Thorp </PERSON> said. Separately, <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> disclosed that `` an entity related to the <ORGANIZATION> Bass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>'' has requested government approval to acquire more than 50 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION>'s outstanding shares.
