<HEAD>Bankers Stress Need For Global Harmony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The world economy is `` on a much more solid footing'' thanks to past efforts among major industrialized nations to coordinate international policies, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told a gathering of bankers and businessmen attending the 34th annual <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, which began Monday and runs through Wednesday, that inflation remained low and trade imbalances were narrowing because of global harmony. In fact, he said, by working together to stabilize exchange rates and coordinate economic policies, the major industrialized nations withstood the worst effects of last October's global stock market collapse. `` It would have been easy for each of us to turn inward and focus on short-term measures to address immediate domestic needs,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said Monday. Instead, he said, the nations `` pulled together and intensified ... efforts to find a compatible and reinforcing set of policies to achieve common goals. `` Since that time, strengthened underlying policy actions have been reflected in enhanced stability of exchange markets,'' he said. `` ... The world economy ... is on a much more solid footing.'' While many conference participants echoed those sentiments Monday, others called upon corporate America to work more on its own to sharpen overseas competitiveness. `` Of course <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> industry owes a large part of these improvements to the weakness of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar. -LRB- But -RRB- the supportive strength of the exchange rates can fade as fast as it has arrived,'' said West German businessmen <PERSON> Dieter </PERSON> <PERSON> Spethmann </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Thyssen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dusseldorf </LOCATION>, in prepared remarks. He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses have more going for them than some of their foreign competitors, including a mobile labor force, flexible labor costs, favorable energy costs and the largest single market in the world. <PERSON> Yotaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Kobayashi </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Fuji </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, said, `` For survival in this volatile global business environment, not only American corporations, but businesses around the world are making significant efforts to expand from their geographic area of strength into other major markets of the world. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> seeks to provide leaders of the top commercial banks and businesses in about 20 different countries with a chance to confer with government officials on topics affecting the world economy as a whole, and the international banking industry in particular. Besides <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> and other central bankers were among those scheduled to attend closed-door `` think sessions'' and speeches. At the opening sessions Monday, the main theme was global cooperation and competitiveness. `` If a deficit country reins in domestic consumption too much, a recession can result,'' said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Seipp </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> IMC </ORGANIZATION>, in a prepared statement. `` On the other hand, if domestic demand in surplus countries is stimulated too much, this could then create the threat of renewed inflation.'' <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON>, chairman of the Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, agreed: `` Each of the problems in question is a matter of common concern, in that each has spillover consequences for the other.'' The bankers, though, said politics was among the obstacles standing in the way of global harmony. `` Even when there is agreement on the objectives ... there may well be difficulties in undoing arduously worked out domestic compromises, or in obtaining timely domestic action where policy-making is decentralized,'' <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON> said. Specifically, he called upon the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to reduce its large federal budget deficit as a way of keeping interest rates down and narrowing its trade gap. He also said <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> should work toward stimulating their economies. In his address Monday, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said steps taken beginning in September 1985 to adjust currency rates were largely responsible for improved economic conditions today. At that time, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its four major trading partners agreed to devalue the dollar to help reduce the spiraling <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit and stave off protectionist legislation. Last year, however, that same group agreed that further declines in the dollar's value would be `` counterproductive.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> noted the most recent March trade figures showed significant improvement, dropping to $ 9.7 billion _ its lowest level in three years _ on the strength of record <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports. `` The success -LRB- of the 1985 gathering -RRB- ... created certain momentum that led to further progress,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said, pointing to other, subsequent meetings.
