<HEAD>Chrysler, UAW Sign Two-Year Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN L. ADLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The signing of a two-year contract between <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> union </ORGANIZATION> has one union executive wondering how the company will fare in its new era. `` The test will really come now as to the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> management's ability to manage,'' <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said Monday after the contract was signed at a ceremony. `` It's been somewhat fortunate with a great deal of assistance, from workers, suppliers and from the economy,'' he said. `` ... Now they're on their own.'' <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> echoed a point made by <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON>, who said the signing ceremony never would have been possible without great sacrifice on the part of all involved with <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> over the last nine years. `` I think <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> is a good example where cooperation from the plant floor on up contributed immensely'' to saving the company, <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> said. Another sign that <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> is recovered from the financial problems that pushed it toward bankruptcy in 1979 is the realignment of the Chrysler-UAW contract with those at <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said. The common expiration date of national labor agreements at the Big Three gives the union an advantage in picking a company to target for a pattern agreement. <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers were hurt financially by being out of synch with <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, but under the circumstances, there was no choice. `` Many of the benefits the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers would have gotten had to go by the wayside because we had to work to save the company,'' <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said. `` They are back making profits and they are back on a level playing field as <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> points out. So they can get back to the business of competing,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> said the two sides recognize <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s mission. `` I think we all realize we're in a very competitive ball game in the future and that's going to result in good cooperative efforts to make sure we stay in the ball game,'' he said. The agreement covering 66,000 workers took effect May 16 after being approved by just 54 percent of the covered workers. One unit, the skilled trades workers, voted down the agreement, but their objections were dealt with. `` I do n't think we should dwell on the question of percentage,'' <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> said. `` It's a question now of what happens from this point forward.'' Chrylser and the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> began early negotiations April 18 as a way to calm rising tensions brought on by <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s consideration of a $ 2 billion offer for its 28,000-worker <ORGANIZATION> Acustar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> parts subsidiary and the company's decision to close a 5,500-worker assembly plant in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis </LOCATION>. The tentative agreement was reached May 4 and eliminated the possibility of a strike in September, which observers said would have been likely because of the anger of rank-and-file workers over the proposed <ORGANIZATION> Acustar </ORGANIZATION> sale and the <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> closing. <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> said the turmoil during negotiations and that 50 percent of the rank and file failed to vote during the ratification process contributed to the low percentage of approval.
